etym: Pseudonym: mid 19th century: from French pseudonyme, from Greek pseudonymos, from pseudes false + onoma name.
def: a fictitious name, especially one used by an author (pen name)

etym: Portmanteau: mid 16th century: from French portemanteau, from porter carry + manteau mantle.
def: a large travelling bag, typically made of stiff leather and opening into two equal parts

etym: Schmutz: iddish shmuts or German Schmutz .
def: dirt or a similar unpleasant substance

etym: Poppycock: mid 19th century: from Dutch dialect pappekak, from pap soft + kak dung.
def: nonsense (nonsense)

etym: Doldrums: late 18th century (as doldrum dull, sluggish person): perhaps from dull
def: a state or period of stagnation or depression (depression)

etym: Roustabout: mid 19th century: from the verb roust
def: an unskilled or casual labourer (rouseabout)

etym: Miasma: mid 17th century: from Greek, literally defilement, from miainein pollute.
def: an unpleasant or unhealthy smell or vapour (stink)

etym: Hokum: arly 20th century: of unknown origin.
def: nonsense

etym: Curmudgeon: ate 16th century: of unknown origin.
def: a bad-tempered or surly person (crank)

etym: Highfalutin: mid 19th century (originally US): perhaps from high
def: (especially of speech, writing, or ideas) pompous or pretentious (pretentious)

etym: Nitwit: early 20th century: apparently from nit
def: a silly or foolish person (often as a general term of abuse) (nit)

etym: Kismet: early 19th century: from Turkish, from Arabic qisma division, portion, lot, from qasama to divide.
def: destiny; fate (fate)

etym: Rigmarole: mid 18th century: apparently an alteration of ragman roll, originally denoting a legal document recording a list of offences.
def: a lengthy and complicated procedure (fuss)

etym: Logorrhea: early 20th century: from Greek logos word + rhoia flow.
def: a tendency to extreme loquacity

etym: Bonkers: 940s: of unknown origin.
def: mad; crazy

etym: Pachyderm: mid 19th century: from French pachyderme, from Greek pakhudermos, from pakhus thick + derma skin.
def: a very large mammal with thick skin, especially an elephant, rhinoceros, or hippopotamus

etym: Fracas: early 18th century: French, from fracasser, from Italian fracassare make an uproar.
def: a noisy disturbance or quarrel (disturbance)

etym: Humdinger: arly 20th century (originally US): of unknown origin.
def: a remarkable or outstanding person or thing of its kind

etym: Loophole: late 16th century (denoting an arrow slit): from obsolete loop embrasure + hole
def: an ambiguity or inadequacy in the law or a set of rules (escape clause)

etym: Ricochet: mid 18th century: from French, of unknown origin.
def: (of a bullet or other projectile) rebound off a surface

etym: Fuddy-duddy: arly 20th century (originally dialect): of unknown origin.
def: a person who is very old-fashioned and pompous (conservative)

etym: Rapscallion: late 17th century: alteration of earlier rascallion, perhaps from rascal
def: a mischievous person (rascal)

etym: Mid 19th century (in sense 3); sense 1 is imitative; sense 2, sense 3 are from wee1, by reduplication.
def: any of a number of birds with a call that resembles the word peewee (magpie lark)

etym: Colossus: late Middle English: via Latin from Greek kolossos (applied by Herodotus to the statues of Egyptian temples).
def: a statue that is much bigger than life size

etym: Schmooze: late 19th century (as a verb): from Yiddish shmuesn converse, chat.
def: talk intimately and cosily; gossip

etym: Ruffian: late 15th century: from Old French ruffian, from Italian ruffiano, perhaps from dialect rofia scab, scurf, of Germanic origin.
def: a violent person, especially one involved in crime (thug)

etym: Blob: late Middle English (denoting a bubble): perhaps symbolic of a drop of liquid; compare with blotch.
def: a drop of a thick liquid or viscous substance (drop)

etym: Supercilious: early 16th century: from Latin superciliosus haughty, from supercilium eyebrow.
def: behaving or looking as though one thinks one is superior to others (arrogant)

etym: Superfluous: late Middle English: from Latin superfluus, from super- over + fluere to flow.
def: unnecessary, especially through being more than enough (surplus)

etym: Eucatastrophe: id 20th century: said to have been coined by Tolkien.
def: a sudden and favourable resolution of events in a story; a happy ending

etym: Flabbergasted: ate 18th century: of unknown origin.
def: surprise (someone) greatly; astonish (astonish)

etym: Lackadaisical: mid 18th century (also in the sense feebly sentimental): from lackaday
def: lacking enthusiasm and determination; carelessly lazy (careless)

etym: Panache: mid 16th century: from French, from Italian pennacchio, from late Latin pinnaculum, diminutive of pinna feather.
def: flamboyant confidence of style or manner (flamboyance)

etym: Grandiloquent: late 16th century: from Latin grandiloquus, literally grand-speaking, from grandis grand + loqui speak. The ending was altered in English by association with eloquent
def: pompous or extravagant in language, style, or manner, especially in a way that is intended to impress (pompous)

etym: Diaphanous: early 17th century: from medieval Latin diaphanus, from Greek diaphanes, from dia through + phainein to show.
def: (especially of fabric) light, delicate, and translucent (sheer)

etym: Apoplectic: early 17th century: from French apoplectique or late Latin apoplecticus, from Greek apoplektikos, from apoplessein disable by a stroke.
def: overcome with anger; furious (furious)

etym: Gumshoe: early 20th century: from gumshoes in the sense sneakers, suggesting stealth.
def: a detective

etym: Junket: late Middle English: from Old French jonquette 'rush basket', from jonc 'rush', from Latin juncus . Originally denoting a rush basket, especially one for fish (remaining in dialect use), the term also denoted a cream cheese, formerly made in a rush basket or served on a rush mat. A later extended sense,'feast, merrymaking', gave rise to sense 2 of the noun.
def: a dish of sweetened and flavoured curds of milk

etym: Copacetic: arly 20th century: of unknown origin.
def: in excellent order

etym: Gimcrack: Middle English gibecrake, of unknown origin. Originally a noun, the term denoted some kind of inlaid work in wood, later a fanciful notion or mechanical contrivance, hence a knick-knack.
def: showy but cheap or badly made (shoddy)

etym: Impromptu: mid 17th century (as an adverb): from French, from Latin in promptu'in readiness', from promptus (see prompt).
def: done without being planned or rehearsed (unrehearsed)

etym: Lambasted: mid 17th century (in the sense beat, thrash): from lam
def: criticize (someone or something) harshly (criticize)

etym: Dodecahedron: late 16th century: from Greek dodekaedron, neuter (used as a noun) of dodekaedros twelve-faced.
def: a three-dimensional shape having twelve plane faces, in particular a regular solid figure with twelve equal pentagonal faces

etym: Heyday: late 16th century (denoting good spirits or passion): from archaic heyday!, an exclamation of joy, surprise, etc.
def: the period of a person's or thing's greatest success, popularity, activity, or vigour (prime)

etym: Mufti: late 16th century: from Arabic mufti, active participle of 'afta'decide a point of law'.
def: a Muslim legal expert who is empowered to give rulings on religious matters (mufti)

etym: Haphazard: late 16th century: from hap
def: lacking any obvious principle of organization (random)

etym: Guffaw: early 18th century (originally Scots): imitative.
def: a loud and hearty laugh (belly laugh)

etym: Idiom: ate 16th century: from French idiome, or via late Latin from Greek idioma private property, peculiar phraseology, from idiousthai make one's own, from idios own, private.
def: a group of words established by usage as having a meaning not deducible from those of the individual words (e.g. over the moon, see the light ) (expression)

etym: Razzle-dazzle: late 19th century: reduplication of dazzle
def: another term for (razzmatazz)

etym: Serendipity: 1754: coined by Horace Walpole, suggested by The Three Princes of Serendip, the title of a fairy tale in which the heroes were always making discoveries, by accidents and sagacity, of things they were not in quest of.
def: the occurrence and development of events by chance in a happy or beneficial way (chance)

etym: Kaleidoscope: early 19th century: from Greek kalos beautiful + eidos form + -scope
def: a toy consisting of a tube containing mirrors and pieces of coloured glass or paper, whose reflections produce changing patterns when the tube is rotated (-scope)

etym: Crescendo: late 18th century: Italian, present participle of crescere to increase, from Latin crescere grow.
def: a gradual increase in loudness in a piece of music

etym: Diphthong: late Middle English: from French diphtongue, via late Latin from Greek diphthongos, from di- twice + phthongos voice, sound.
def: a sound formed by the combination of two vowels in a single syllable, in which the sound begins as one vowel and moves towards another (as in coin, loud, and side )

etym: Adagio: Italian, from ad agio at ease.
def: (especially as a direction) in slow time

etym: Haboob: late 19th century: from Arabic habub blowing furiously.
def: a violent and oppressive wind blowing in summer in Sudan and elsewhere, bringing sand from the desert

etym: Flippant: early 17th century: from flip
def: not showing a serious or respectful attitude (frivolous)

etym: Pomposity: late Middle English: from Old French pompeux full of grandeur, from late Latin pomposus, from pompa pomp.
def: the quality of being pompous; self-importance (self-importance)

etym: Hornswoggle: arly 19th century (originally US): of unknown origin.
def: get the better of (someone) by cheating or deception

etym: Pugnacious: mid 17th century: from Latin pugnax, pugnac- (from pugnare to fight, from pugnus fist) + -ious
def: eager or quick to argue, quarrel, or fight (combative)

etym: Gadzooks: late 17th century: alteration of God's hooks, i.e. the nails by which Christ was fastened to the cross; see gad
def: an exclamation of surprise or annoyance (gad)

etym: Menagerie: late 17th century: from French menagerie, from menage (see menage)
def: a collection of wild animals kept in captivity for exhibition (menage)

etym: Razzmatazz: late 19th century: probably an alteration of razzle-dazzle
def: noisy, showy, and exciting activity and display designed to attract and impress (razzle-dazzle)

etym: Mollycoddle: mid 19th century: from molly girl or prostitute (see moll
def: treat (someone) in an indulgent or overprotective way (pamper)

etym: Gazebo: mid 18th century: perhaps humorously from gaze
def: a small building, especially one in the garden of a house, that gives a wide view of the surrounding area (summer house)

etym: Digeridoo: 1920s: imitative; from an Aboriginal language of Arnhem Land.
def: an Australian Aboriginal wind instrument in the form of a long wooden tube, traditionally made from a hollow branch, which is blown to produce a deep, resonant sound, varied by rhythmic accents of timbre and volume

etym: Pettifogger: mid 16th century: from petty
def: an inferior legal practitioner, especially one who deals with petty cases or employs dubious practices (petty)

etym: Cacophony: mid 17th century: from French cacophonie, from Greek kakophonia, from kakophonos ill-sounding, from kakos bad + phone sound.
def: a harsh discordant mixture of sounds (din)

etym: Jabberwocky: early 20th century: from the title of a nonsense poem in Lewis Carroll's Through the Looking Glass (1871).
def: invented or meaningless language; nonsense

etym: Fandango: mid 18th century: Spanish, of unknown origin.
def: a lively Spanish dance for two people, typically accompanied by castanets or tambourine

etym: Jacuzzi: 1960s: named after Candido Jacuzzi ( c.  190386), Italian-born American inventor.
def: a large bath with a system of underwater jets of water to massage the body

etym: Jitney: arly 20th century (originally denoting a five-cent piece): of unknown origin.
def: a bus or other vehicle carrying passengers for a low fare

etym: Froufrou: late 19th century: from French, imitative of the sound of a woman walking in a dress.
def: frills or other ornamentation, particularly of women's clothes

etym: Fricassee: French fricassee, feminine past participle of fricasser cut up and cook in sauce (probably a blend of frire to fry and casser to break).
def: a dish of stewed or fried pieces of meat served in a thick white sauce

etym: Azure: Middle English (denoting a blue dye): from Old French asur, azur, from medieval Latin azzurum, azolum, from Arabic al the + lazaward (from Persian lazward lapis lazuli).
def: bright blue in colour like a cloudless sky (blue)

etym: Jetsam: late 16th century (as jetson ): from jettison
def: unwanted material or goods that have been thrown overboard from a ship and washed ashore, especially material that has been discarded to lighten the vessel (jettison)

etym: Finicky: early 19th century: from finical
def: (of a person) fussy about their needs or requirements (fussy)

etym: Cornucopia: early 16th century: from late Latin, from Latin cornu copiae horn of plenty (a mythical horn able to provide whatever is desired).
def: a symbol of plenty consisting of a goat's horn overflowing with flowers, fruit, and corn

etym: Canoodle: id 19th century (originally US): of unknown origin.
def: kiss and cuddle amorously

etym: Hogwash: mid 15th century: from hog
def: nonsense (hog)

etym: Huzzah: ate 16th century: perhaps used originally as a sailor's cry when hauling.
def: used to express approval or delight

etym: Sobriquet: mid 17th century: French, originally in the sense tap under the chin, of unknown origin.
def: a person's nickname

etym: Majordomo: late 16th century: via Spanish and Italian from medieval Latin major domus highest official of the household.
def: the chief steward of a large household

etym: Donnybrook: id 19th century: from the name of a suburb of Dublin, Ireland, formerly famous for its annual fair.
def: a scene of uproar and disorder; a heated argument

etym: Slipshod: late 16th century (originally in the sense wearing slippers or loose shoes): from the verb slip
def: characterized by a lack of care, thought, or organization (careless)

etym: Demitasse: mid 19th century: from French, literally half-cup.
def: a small coffee cup

etym: Palindrome: early 17th century: from Greek palindromos running back again, from palin again + drom- (from dramein to run).
def: a word, phrase, or sequence that reads the same backwards as forwards, e.g. madam or nurses run

etym: Bupkis: from Yiddish.
def: nothing at all

etym: Knickerbocker: mid 19th century (originally in sense 2): named after Diedrich Knickerbocker, pretended author of W. Irving's History of New York (1809). Sense 1 is said to have arisen from the resemblance of knickerbockers to the knee breeches worn by Dutch men in George Cruikshank's illustrations in Irving's book.
def: loose-fitting breeches gathered at the knee or calf

etym: Riposte: early 18th century: from French risposte (noun), risposter (verb), from Italian risposta response.
def: a quick, clever reply to an insult or criticism (retort)

etym: Jujubes: late Middle English: from French, or from medieval Latin jujuba, based on Greek zizuphos .
def: the edible berry-like fruit of a Eurasian plant, formerly taken as a cough cure

etym: Babushka: Russian, grandmother.
def: (in Russia) an old woman or grandmother

etym: Brannigan: ate 19th century: of unknown origin; perhaps from the surname Brannigan.
def: a brawl or violent argument

etym: Ragamuffin: Middle English: probably based on rag
def: a person, typically a child, in ragged, dirty clothes (urchin)

etym: Antimacassar: mid 19th century: from anti- + Macassar.
def: a piece of cloth put over the back of a chair to protect it from grease and dirt or as an ornament.

etym: Pagoda: late 16th century: from Portuguese pagode, perhaps based on Persian butkada temple of idols, influenced by Prakrit bhagodi divine.
def: (in India and East Asia) a Hindu or Buddhist temple, typically in the form of a many-tiered tower

etym: Manifesto: mid 17th century: from Italian, from manifestare, from Latin, make public, from manifestus obvious (see manifest)
def: a public declaration of policy and aims, especially one issued before an election by a political party or candidate (platform)

etym: Hodgepodge: late Middle English: alteration of hotchpotch
def: variant of (hotchpotch)

etym: Gibberish: early 16th century: perhaps from gibber
def: unintelligible or meaningless speech or writing; nonsense (nonsense)

etym: Mid 19th century: from the name of the character Mrs Malaprop in Sheridan's play The Rivals (1775) + -ism
def: The mistaken use of a word in place of a similar-sounding one, often with an amusing effect (e.g. dance a flamingo  instead of flamenco ) (solecism).

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French jubile, from late Latin jubilaeus (annus) (year) of jubilee, based on Hebrew yobel, originally ram's-horn trumpet, with which the jubilee year was proclaimed.
def: A special anniversary of an event, especially one celebrating twenty-five or fifty years of a reign or activity (anniversary).

etym: 1920s: from Opelousas in Louisiana, or Palouse, a river in Idaho.
def: A horse of a North American breed having dark spots on a light background.

etym: Late 17th century (as an adverb): reduplication based on hare.
def: Reckless; impetuous (reckless).

etym: Early 20th century: from Latin American Spanish, from Spanish palomino young pigeon, from Latin palumbinus resembling a dove.
def: A pale golden or tan-coloured horse or pony with a white mane and tail, originally bred in the south-western US.

etym: Mid 19th century (denoting a devotee of bullfighting): from Spanish, amateur, past participle of aficioner become fond of used as a noun, based on Latin affectio(n-) (favourable) disposition towards (see affection).
def: A person who is very knowledgeable and enthusiastic about an activity, subject, or pastime (connoisseur).

etym: Late Middle English (in the sense person who loiters aimlessly): from mooch + -er.
def: A person who lives off others without giving anything in return (mooch).

etym: Early 16th century (denoting a form of argument involving a choice between equally unfavourable alternatives): via Latin from Greek dilemma, from di- twice + lemma premise.
def: A situation in which a difficult choice has to be made between two or more alternatives, especially ones that are equally undesirable (quandary).

etym: Said to have been invented by Diana Vreeland, fashion editor of Harper's Bazaar in the 1930s.
def: An attractive combination of vitality and glamour.

etym: Mid 19th century: from Italian, literally bottle, flask, in the phrase far fiasco, literally make a bottle, figuratively fail in a performance: the reason for the figurative sense is unexplained.
def: A complete failure, especially a ludicrous or humiliating one (failure).

etym: Late 16th century (in the sense boiling): from Latin ebullient- boiling up, from the verb ebullire, from e- (variant of ex- ) out + bullire to boil.
def: Cheerful and full of energy (exuberant).

etym: Early 19th century: related to gibber.
def: Talk in a rapid and excited way that is difficult to understand (gibber).

etym: 1960s: perhaps named after Hiram Codd, who invented a bottle for fizzy drinks (1875); the derivation remains unconfirmed.
def: Nonsense.

etym: Late Middle English: from in kenebowe in Middle English, probably from Old Norse.
def: With hands on the hips and elbows turned outwards.

etym: Late 16th century: from Greek ephēmeros (see ephemera) + -al.
def: Lasting for a very short time (transitory).

etym: Mid 16th century: from Old French en gogues, from en in + the plural of gogue fun.
def: Very eager or curious to hear or see something (eager).

etym: Mid 16th century (denoting a simpleton): variant of cockscomb, in the sense ‘jester's cap’ (resembling a cockscomb), hence ‘a jester, a fool’.
def: A vain and conceited man; a dandy (cockscomb).

etym: Mid 16th century: symbolic reduplication.
def: Nonsensical or insincere talk.

etym: Late Middle English: via medieval Latin from Arabic al-'iksir, from al the + 'iksir from Greek xerion powder for drying wounds (from xeros dry).
def: A magical or medicinal potion (potion).

etym: Late 17th century: said to be named from a former watermark representing a fool's cap.
def: A size of paper, about 330  200 (or 400) mm.

etym: Mid 18th century: probably of Celtic origin and related to Welsh bwci bo bogey, the Devil, bwci hobgoblin and Cornish bucca.
def: An object of fear or alarm; a bogey.

etym: Mid 16th century: of unknown origin.
def: A clumsy or awkward youth.

etym: Middle English: apparently from goose.
def: A fine, filmy substance consisting of cobwebs spun by small spiders, seen especially in autumn (cobweb).

etym: Middle English: from Old French gargouille throat, also gargoyle (because of the water passing through the throat and mouth of the figure); related to Greek gargarizein to gargle (imitating the sounds made in the throat).
def: A grotesque carved human or animal face or figure projecting from the gutter of a building, typically acting as a spout to carry water clear of a wall.

etym: 1940s (originally US): of unknown origin.
def: A gadget, especially one whose name the speaker does not know or cannot recall.

etym: Mid 19th century: of unknown origin.
def: A person, typically a child, who behaves badly but in an amusingly mischievous rather than harmful way; a rascal.

etym: Early 20th century: from Hawaiian mu'u mu'u, literally cut off.
def: A woman's loose, brightly coloured dress, especially one traditionally worn in Hawaii.

etym: Mid 17th century: via Portuguese amouco, from Malay amok rushing in a frenzy. Early use was as a noun denoting a Malay in a homicidal frenzy.
def: Behave uncontrollably and disruptively (rampage).

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French, or Latin machinatio-, from machinat- contrived (see machinate).
def: A plot or scheme (machinate).

etym: Late 17th century: from early modern Dutch (denoting a mythical whirlpool in the Arctic Ocean, west of Norway), from maalen grind, whirl + stroom stream.
def: A powerful whirlpool in the sea or a river (whirlpool).

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin sesquipedalis'a foot and a half long', from sesqui- (see sesqui-) + pes, ped-'foot'.
def: Characterized by long words; long-winded.

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin dirigere to direct + -ible.
def: Capable of being steered, guided, or directed (-ible).

etym: Early 20th century (originally servicemen's slang): blend of doodad and hickey.
def: A small object or gadget, especially one whose precise name the speaker cannot recall (doodad).

etym: Late Middle English: probably imitative of idle chatter.
def: A frivolous, flighty, or excessively talkative person.

etym: Mid 19th century: probably based on discompose or discomfit.
def: Disconcert or confuse (someone) (discompose).

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin resplendent- shining out, from the verb resplendere, from re- (expressing intensive force) + splendere to glitter.
def: Attractive and impressive through being richly colourful or sumptuous (splendid).

etym: Early 17th century: from Italian and Spanish laguna, from Latin lacuna (see lacuna).
def: A stretch of salt water separated from the sea by a low sandbank or coral reef (inlet).

etym: Early 17th century (in the sense'play on words, pun'): diminutive of obsolete quib'a petty objection', probably from Latin quibus, dative and ablative plural of qui, quae, quod'who, what, which', frequently used in legal documents and so associated with subtle distinctions or verbal niceties.
def: A slight objection or criticism (protest).

etym: Late 19th century: of unknown origin.
def: Braided trimming in a zigzag pattern, used as decoration on clothes.

etym: Late 19th century: from Egyptian Arabic lufa, denoting the plant.
def: The fibrous matter of the fluid-transport system of a marrow-like fruit, which is dried and used as a bath sponge.

etym: Spanish.
def: A cold Spanish soup made from tomatoes, peppers, and other salad vegetables.

etym: Early 19th century: superseding earlier tag-rag and tag and rag (see rag, see tag).
def: Untidy, disorganized, or incongruously varied in character (rag).

etym: 1920s (originally US): of unknown origin.
def: Nonsense

etym: Early 21st century: with reference to a misinterpretation of acorn.
def: A word or phrase that results from a mishearing or misinterpretation of another, an element of the original being substituted for one which sounds very similar (e.g. tow the line instead of toe the line ) (acorn).

etym: Middle English: of unknown origin.
def: A showy thing, especially one that is useless or worthless.

etym: Mid 19th century: diminutive of imitative piff-.
def: Nonsense (nonsense).

etym: 1960s: probably from US slang doodle excrement + squat.
def: Anything (squat).

etym: 16th century: from Latin incredulus (from in- not + credulus believing, trusting, from credere believe) + -ous.
def: (of a person or their manner) unwilling or unable to believe something (disbelieving).

etym: Early 17th century: from Tamil kattumaram, literally tied wood.
def: A yacht or other boat with twin hulls in parallel.

etym: Mid 19th century (as a verb): alteration of chasse.
def: Walk in an ostentatious yet casual manner, typically with exaggerated movements of the hips and shoulders (chasse).

etym: Mid 17th century: modern Latin (denoting the place of all demons, in Milton's Paradise Lost ), from pan- ‘all’ + Greek daimōn ‘demon’.
def: Wild and noisy disorder or confusion; uproar.

etym: Mid 17th century (in the sense fit for a feast, festive): from Latin convivialis, from convivium a feast, from con- with + vivere live.
def: (of an atmosphere or event) friendly, lively, and enjoyable (friendly).

etym: Late 16th century (denoting an unauthorized trader trespassing on the rights of a trade monopoly): from inter- ‘amid’ + -loper as in archaic landloper ‘vagabond’ (from Middle Dutch landlooper).
def: A person who becomes involved in a place or situation where they are not wanted or are considered not to belong (intruder).

etym: Early 17th century: alteration of Algonquian pessemmins.
def: An edible fruit that resembles a large tomato and has very sweet flesh.

etym: Taken aback, shaken.
def: Greatly astonish or amaze (astonish).

etym: Late 19th century: named after General Ambrose Burnside (182481), American army officer.
def: A moustache in combination with whiskers on the cheeks but no beard on the chin.

etym: Late Middle English (in the mythological sense): via Latin from Greek alkuōn'kingfisher' (also halkuōn, by association with hals'sea' and kuōn'conceiving').
def: Denoting a period of time in the past that was idyllically happy and peaceful (serene).

etym: Late 16th century (in sense 3): from dialect logger ‘block of wood for hobbling a horse’ + head.
def: A reddish-brown turtle with a very large head, occurring chiefly in warm seas.

etym: Middle English: from Old Norse rannsaka, from rann house + a second element related to skja seek.
def: Go through (a place) stealing things and causing damage (plunder).

etym: Mid 18th century: fanciful formation based on the given name of Ambrose Philips (died 1749), an English writer whose pastorals were ridiculed by Pope and others.
def: Lacking energy, strength, or courage; weak or ineffectual.

etym: Early 19th century: from Turkish fes (perhaps via French fez ), named after Fez, once the chief place of manufacture.
def: A flat-topped conical red hat with a black tassel on top, worn by men in some Muslim countries (formerly the Turkish national headdress) (Fez).

etym: Early 16th century: from Old French mayhem (see maim). The sense ‘disorder’ (originally US) dates from the late 19th century.
def: Violent or extreme disorder; chaos (chaos).

etym: Late 16th century: from Spanish sasafras, based on Latin saxifraga saxifrage.
def: A deciduous North American tree with aromatic leaves and bark. The leaves are infused to make tea or ground into file.

etym: Late 17th century: perhaps from the given name Nicholas or from Nicodemus (by association with the Pharisee of this name, and his naive questioning of Christ; compare with French nicodeme simpleton).
def: A foolish or stupid person.

etym: Mid 16th century: from archaic French galimafree unappetizing dish, perhaps from Old French galer have fun + Picard mafrer eat copious quantities.
def: A confused jumble or medley of things.

etym: Early 20th century: Yiddish, from Russian nudnyi tedious.
def: A pestering, nagging, or irritating person; a bore.

etym: Mid 19th century: probably of dialect origin; flummock to make untidy, confuse is recorded in western counties and the north Midlands.
def: Bewildered or perplexed (baffle).

etym: Early 19th century (in the sense drink together): from archaic hob or nob, hob and nob, probably meaning give and take, used by two people drinking to each other's health, from dialect hab nab have or not have.
def: Mix socially, especially with those of perceived higher social status.

etym: Late 18th century: from Latin ore rotundo with rounded mouth.
def: (of a person's voice) resonant and imposing (deep).

etym: Mid 19th century: abbreviation of lunatic.
def: A mad or silly person (lunatic).

etym: Mexican Spanish, literally trinket.
def: A tortilla rolled round a savoury filling and deep-fried.

etym: Eavesdropping is the act of secretly or stealthily listening to the private conversation or communications of others without their consent. The practice is widely regarded as unethical, and in many jurisdictions is illegal.
def: Secretly listen to a conversation (spy).

etym: Mid 16th century (denoting a body of Macedonian infantry): via Latin from Greek.
def: A body of troops or police officers standing or moving in close formation.

etym: Early 17th century: compare with obsolete Scots dunder, dunner resounding noise; related to din.
def: A stupid person (din).

etym: Late 15th century: reduplication of mash.
def: A confused mixture (jumble).

etym: Late 17th century (as a mystical word engraved and used as a charm to ward off illness): from Latin, first recorded in a 2nd-century poem by Q. Serenus Sammonicus, from a Greek base.
def: A word said by conjurors when performing a magic trick (hocus-pocus).

etym: Mid 19th century: from archaic squeege to press, strengthened form of squeeze.
def: A scraping implement with a rubber-edged blade set on a handle, typically used for cleaning windows (squeeze).

etym: Mid 17th century: from French lampon, said to be from lampons let us drink (used as a refrain), from lamper gulp down, nasalized form of laper to lap (liquid).
def: Publicly criticize (someone or something) by using ridicule, irony, or sarcasm (satirize).

etym: Mid 18th century (as Mumbo Jumbo, denoting a supposed African idol): of unknown origin; the current sense dates from the late 19th century.
def: Language or ritual causing or intended to cause confusion or bewilderment (nonsense).

etym: Late 16th century: via Latin from Greek hippokampos, from hippos horse + kampos sea monster.
def: The elongated ridges on the floor of each lateral ventricle of the brain, thought to be the centre of emotion, memory, and the autonomic nervous system.

etym: Swedish, from smorgas (slice of) bread and butter (from smor butter + gas goose, lump of butter) + bord table.
def: A range of open sandwiches and delicacies served as hors d'oeuvres or a buffet.

etym: Early 20th century (as a verb): from Yiddish shlepn drag, from Middle High German sleppen .
def: Haul or carry (something heavy or awkward) (schlepper).

etym: Early 19th century (denoting a water butt on the deck of a ship, providing drinking water): from scuttled butt . Sailors would traditionally exchange gossip when they gathered at the scuttlebutt for a drink of water.
def: Rumour; gossip.

etym: 1940s: boondock from Tagalog bundok mountain.
def: Rough or isolated country.

etym: Late Middle English: via Latin from Greek huperbole (see hyperbola.
def: Exaggerated statements or claims not meant to be taken literally (exaggeration).

etym: Mid 19th century: from curly.
def: A decorative curl or twist in calligraphy or in the design of an object (curly).

etym: 1940s (originally denoting a design left by a transfer): probably an alteration of decalcomania.
def: Ridiculous; implausible (decalcomania).

etym: Early 17th century: pseudo-Spanish alteration of the obsolete noun desperate . Both desperate and desperado originally denoted a person in despair or in a desperate situation, hence someone made reckless by despair.
def: A desperate or reckless person, especially a criminal (bandit).

etym: Early 17th century: Latin, from apparare make ready for, from ad- towards + parare make ready.
def: The technical equipment or machinery needed for a particular activity or purpose (equipment).

etym: Late 18th century: alteration of and per se and  & by itself is and , formerly chanted as an aid to learning the sign.
def: The sign & (standing for and, as in Smith & Co., or the Latin et, as in &c. ).

etym: Early 19th century: from Chinese ketou, from ke knock + tou head.
def: Act in an excessively subservient manner (grovel).

etym: Early 17th century (denoting a stew made of different kinds of meat): from French, literally rotten pot.
def: A mixture of dried petals and spices placed in a bowl to perfume a room (mixture).

etym: Late 18th century: from ballista.
def: Relating to projectiles or their flight (ballista).

etym: Mid 19th century: from the Greek name Kalliope (see Calliope.
def: An American keyboard instrument resembling an organ but with the notes produced by steam whistles, formerly used on showboats and in travelling fairs (Calliope).

etym: Early 16th century: from Italian arcipelago, from Greek arkhi- chief + pelagos sea. The word was originally used as a proper name ( the Archipelago the Aegean Sea): the general sense arose because the Aegean Sea is notable for its large numbers of islands.
def: An extensive group of islands.

etym: Early 17th century: from Latin lugubris (from lugere mourn) + -ous.
def: Looking or sounding sad and dismal (mournful).

etym: From Portuguese nababo or Spanish nabab, from Urdu; see also nawab.
def: A Muslim official or governor under the Mogul empire (tycoon).

etym: 1930s: perhaps an alteration of Yiddish arumfartzen fart about.
def: Waste time; idle or busy oneself aimlessly.

etym: From Tamil milaku-tanni pepper water.
def: A spicy meat soup originally made in India.

etym: 1980s: from gob.
def: Utterly astonished; astounded (gob).

etym: Late 19th century: from French, probably imitative.
def: A noisy and overexcited reaction or response to something.

etym: Mid 16th century: from French bouffon, from Italian buffone, from medieval Latin buffo clown. Originally recorded as a rare Scots word for a kind of pantomime dance, the term later (late 16th century) denoted a professional jester.
def: A ridiculous but amusing person; a clown.

etym: Late 16th century: from Portuguese moncao, from Arabic mawsim season, from wasama to mark, brand.
def: A seasonal prevailing wind in the region of South and South East Asia, blowing from the south-west between May and September and bringing rain (the wet monsoon ), or from the north-east between October and April (the dry monsoon ).

etym: Early 19th century (originally US, especially with reference to success when mining): from Spanish, literally fair weather, prosperity, from Latin bonus good.
def: A situation which creates a sudden increase in wealth, good fortune, or profits (windfall).

etym: Late 19th century (originally US): apparently an alteration of voodoo.
def: Voodoo or witchcraft (witchcraft).

etym: Mid 16th century: from swash.
def: A swashbuckling person (swash).

etym: Early 17th century: from French, from Latin nomenclatura, from nomen name + clatura calling, summoning (from calare to call).
def: The devising or choosing of names for things, especially in a science or other discipline.

etym: Late 16th century: from French rendez-vous! present yourselves!, imperative of se rendre .
def: A meeting at an agreed time and place (meeting).

etym: Early 20th century: from hill.
def: An unsophisticated country person, as associated originally with the remote regions of the Appalachians (country music).

etym: Early 19th century (originally as a noun denoting an ancient Norse warrior who fought with wild or uncontrolled ferocity): from Old Norse berserkr (noun), probably from birn-, bjorn (see bear.
def: Out of control with anger or excitement; wild or frenzied (mad).

etym: Mid 16th century: from French, from accoutrer clothe, equip (see accoutre.
def: An additional item of dress or equipment (accoutre).

etym: Early 17th century: from hax pax max Deus adimax, a pseudo-Latin phrase used as a magic formula by conjurors.
def: Meaningless talk or activity, typically designed to trick someone or conceal the truth of a situation (jargon).

etym: Mid 19th century: from the name of Bumble, the beadle in Dickens's Oliver Twist, + -dom.
def: Officious and pompous behaviour by minor officials (-dom).

etym: Late 16th century: from French pele-mele, from earlier pesle mesle, mesle pesle, reduplication from mesler to mix.
def: In a confused, rushed, or disorderly manner (helter-skelter).

etym: Mid 16th century (originally in the sense to blindfold): from the noun hood.
def: Deceive or trick (deceive).

etym: Late 16th century (denoting a boaster): from Braggadocchio, the name of a braggart in Spenser's The Faerie Queene, from brag.
def: Boastful or arrogant behaviour (brag).

etym: Early 19th century: French, from raconter relate, recount.
def: A person who tells anecdotes in a skilful and amusing way (storyteller).

etym: Mid 19th century: formed irregularly from splendour.
def: Splendid (splendour).

etym: From Hindi and Punjabi, from Sanskrit guru weighty, grave (compare with Latin gravis ), hence elder, teacher.
def: A Hindu spiritual teacher (teacher).

etym: Mid 17th century: from modern Latin infinitesimus, from Latin infinitus (see infinite.
def: Extremely small (minute).

etym: Late 17th century: from Chinese (Cantonese dialect) kam kwat little orange.
def: An orange-like fruit related to the citruses, with an edible sweet rind and acid pulp.

etym: Late 16th century (in .
def: Women's baggy trousers gathered at the ankles.

etym: Middle English: reduplication based on hurl.
def: Busy, boisterous activity (bustle).

etym: Early 19th century: fanciful formation from colic.
def: Stomach pain or queasiness (colic).

etym: Early 19th century: from Greek anthropomorphos (see anthropomorphous.
def: Relating to or characterized by anthropomorphism (anthropomorphous).

etym: Late 18th century (in the sense perpendicularity, steadiness): from French, from a plomb according to a plumb line.
def: Self-confidence or assurance, especially when in a demanding situation (poise).

etym: Late 17th century: originally used to describe a man wearing blue worsted (instead of formal black silk) stockings; extended to mean in informal dress. Later the term denoted a person who attended the literary assemblies held ( c.  1750) by three London society ladies, where some of the men favoured less formal dress. The women who attended became known as blue-stocking ladies or blue-stockingers .
def: An intellectual or literary woman.

etym: Old English earwicga, from eare ear + wicga earwig (probably related to wiggle ); the insect was once thought to crawl into the human ear.
def: A small elongated insect with a pair of terminal appendages that resemble pincers.

etym: Mid 18th century: French denouement, from denouer unknot.
def: The final part of a play, film, or narrative in which the strands of the plot are drawn together and matters are explained or resolved (finale).

etym: Late 16th century (in the sense fashionable, stylish): from French gentil well-born. From the 17th century to the 19th century the word was used in such senses as of good social position, having the manners of a well-born person, well bred. The ironic or derogatory implication dates from the 19th century.
def: Characterized by exaggerated or affected politeness, refinement, or respectability (refined).

etym: Early 19th century: perhaps from Scots curfuffle (probably from Scottish Gaelic car twist, bend + imitative Scots fuffle to disorder), or related to Irish cior thual confusion, disorder.
def: A commotion or fuss, especially one caused by conflicting views.

etym: Late Middle English (earlier as pollywiggle ): from poll.
def: A tadpole (poll).

etym: Mid 16th century (denoting old or second-hand clothes): from French friperie, from Old French freperie, from frepe rag, of unknown ultimate origin.
def: Showy or unnecessary ornament in architecture, dress, or language (ostentation).

etym: Late 16th century: from gad.
def: A fly that bites livestock, especially a horsefly, warble fly, or botfly (gad).

etym: Mid 19th century: named after the Marquis Muzio Frangipani, a 16th-century Italian nobleman who invented a perfume for scenting gloves.
def: A tropical American tree or shrub with clusters of fragrant white, pink, or yellow flowers.

etym: Early 20th century (in the sense showiness or pretentious object): from French, of imitative origin.
def: Attempting stylish elegance but achieving only an over-elaborate pretentiousness.

etym: 1950s: from Lady Mondegreen, a misinterpretation of the phrase laid him on the green, from the traditional ballad The Bonny Earl of Murray.
def: A misunderstood or misinterpreted word or phrase resulting from a mishearing of the lyrics of a song.

etym: Mid 16th century: probably a reduplication of hum.
def: Lacking excitement or variety; boringly monotonous (mundane).

etym: Early 16th century (as a noun): via Latin from Greek boukolikos, from boukolos herdsman, from bous ox.
def: Relating to the pleasant aspects of the countryside and country life (rustic).

etym: Late Middle English: from bailie.
def: One's sphere of operations or area of interest (bailie).

etym: Middle English: from Greek epiphainein reveal. The sense relating to the Christian festival is via Old French epiphanie and ecclesiastical Latin epiphania .
def: The manifestation of Christ to the Gentiles as represented by the Magi (Matthew 2:112).

etym: Mid 19th century: extension of Juggernaut.
def: A huge, powerful, and overwhelming force (Juggernaut).

etym: Mid 19th century: from German, literally double-goer.
def: An apparition or double of a living person.

etym: Middle English: from Old French folhardi, from fol foolish + hardi bold (see hardy.
def: Recklessly bold or rash (reckless).

etym: Early 17th century: from Latin scintillat- sparkled, from the verb scintillare, from scintilla spark.
def: Sparkling or shining brightly (sparkling).

etym: Late 15th century (as riff and raff ): from Old French rif et raf one and all, every bit, of Germanic origin.
def: Disreputable or undesirable people (rabble).

etym: Mid 18th century: from Latin flocci, nauci, nihili, pili (words meaning at little value) + -fication.
def: The action or habit of estimating something as worthless (-fication).

etym: Mid 16th century: from Latin, said to be from Greek anemone windflower, literally daughter of the wind, from anemos wind, thought to be so named because the flowers open only when the wind blows.
def: A plant of the buttercup family which typically has brightly coloured flowers and deeply divided leaves (sea anemone).

etym: Early 18th century: modern Latin, from Greek borborugmos .
def: A rumbling or gurgling noise made by the movement of fluid and gas in the intestines.

etym: Late Middle English: from heir.
def: A valuable object that has belonged to a family for several generations (heir).

etym: Mid 17th century (in the sense untameable): from late Latin indomitabilis, from in- not + Latin domitare to tame.
def: Impossible to subdue or defeat (invincible).

etym: Late 18th century: via Latin from Greek bibliopoles, from biblion book + poles seller.
def: A person who buys and sells books, especially rare ones.

etym: 1960s: from Yiddish kvetsh (noun), kvetshn (verb), from Middle High German quetschen, literally crush.
def: A person who complains a great deal.

etym: Early 16th century: from French poltron, from Italian poltrone, perhaps from poltro sluggard.
def: An utter coward.

etym: Early 17th century: probably from obsolete fisty relating to the fists or to fist fighting + cuff.
def: Fighting with the fists (cuff).

etym: Late 16th century: from Hebrew Nimrod, the name of the great-grandson of Noah, known for his skill as a hunter (see Gen. 10:8-9).
def: A skilful hunter.

etym: Late 16th century: probably from obsolete bug bogey (of unknown origin) + bear.
def: A cause of obsessive fear, anxiety, or irritation (hate).

etym: Late 16th century (in the sense a petty trick): reduplication of knack.
def: Small worthless objects, especially household ornaments (ornament).

etym: Late 17th century: from Hindi bangla belonging to Bengal, from a type of cottage built for early European settlers in Bengal.
def: A low house having only one storey or, in some cases, upper rooms set in the roof, typically with dormer windows.

etym: 1940s: from US boff roaring success + -o.
def: (of a theatrical production or film, or a review of one) very successful or wholeheartedly commendatory (-o).

etym: Miaowing, miaow.
def: (of a cat) make a shrill howling or wailing noise (howl).

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin non plus not more. The noun originally meant a state in which no more can be said or done.
def: So surprised and confused that one is unsure how to react (surprise).

etym: Early 17th century (originally in the sense physical constitution peculiar to an individual): from Greek idiosunkrasia, from idios own, private + sun with + krasis mixture.
def: A mode of behaviour or way of thought peculiar to an individual (peculiarity).

etym: 1930s: from the noun switch.
def: A change, reversal, or exchange, especially a surprising or deceptive one (switch).

etym: Mid 18th century (as an adjective): via medieval Latin from Greek mnemonikos, from mnemon mindful.
def: A system such as a pattern of letters, ideas, or associations which assists in remembering something.

etym: Mid 17th century: from late Latin abecedarius alphabetical (from the names of the letters a, b, c, d ) + -an.
def: Arranged alphabetically (-an).

etym: Late 16th century: from French apogee or modern Latin apogaeum, from Greek apogaion (diastema), (distance) away from earth, from apo from + gaia, ge earth.
def: The highest point in the development of something; a climax or culmination.

etym: Middle English: from Old French cucu, imitative of its call.
def: A long-tailed, medium-sized bird, typically with a grey or brown back and barred or pale underparts. Many cuckoos lay their eggs in the nests of small songbirds.

etym: Mid 19th century (originally US): hunky from Dutch honk home, base (in games); the origin of dory is unknown.
def: Fine; going well.

etym: Early 19th century: modern Latin, from Latin glabellus (adjective), diminutive of glaber smooth.
def: The smooth part of the forehead above and between the eyebrows.

etym: Late 16th century (as an adverb): a rhyming jingle of unknown origin, perhaps symbolic of running feet or from Middle English skelte hasten.
def: In disorderly haste or confusion (headlong).

etym: Late Middle English (in the sense disaster and distress): from Old French calamite, from Latin calamitas .
def: An event causing great and often sudden damage or distress; a disaster (disaster).

etym: Late 17th century: reduplication of chat.
def: Inconsequential conversation (small talk).

etym: 1940s: perhaps from Gussie, pet form of the given name Augustus .
def: Make someone or something more attractive, especially in a showy or gimmicky way.

etym: Late 16th century: via late Latin from Greek onomatopoiia word-making, from onoma, onomat- name + -poios making (from poiein to make).
def: The formation of a word from a sound associated with what is named (e.g. cuckoo, sizzle ).

etym: Mid 19th century (earlier (Middle English) as juxtaposition ): from French juxtaposer, from Latin juxta next + French poser to place.
def: The fact of two things being seen or placed close together with contrasting effect (comparison).

etym: Early 19th century: alteration of vaquero.
def: A cowboy (vaquero).

etym: Mid 17th century: from French feston, from Italian festone festal ornament, from festum, (plural) festa feast.
def: Adorn (a place) with chains, garlands, or other decorations (decorate).

etym: 1950s: first popularized by a character on the US television programme Howdy Doody (194760). It later became associated with surfing culture and was further popularized by use on the US television cartoon programme Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (198796).
def: Used to express delight or satisfaction.

etym: Late 18th century: from Don Quixote.
def: Extremely idealistic; unrealistic and impractical (idealistic).

etym: Late 16th century: modern Latin, from Greek parabole placing side by side, application, from para- beside + bole a throw (from the verb ballein ).
def: A symmetrical open plane curve formed by the intersection of a cone with a plane parallel to its side. The path of a projectile under the influence of gravity follows a curve of this shape.

etym: Mid 19th century: from Inuit iglu house.
def: A dome-shaped Eskimo house, typically built from blocks of solid snow.

etym: Mid 18th century: from Narragansett msiquatash (plural).
def: An American dish of maize and lima beans boiled together.

etym: Mid 19th century: from Latin, literally thumb or big toe.
def: The innermost digit of a forelimb, especially the thumb in primates.

etym: German Schadenfreude, from Schaden harm + Freude joy.
def: Pleasure derived by someone from another person's misfortune.

etym: Mid 16th century (in the medical sense): via late Latin from Greek plethore, from plethein be full.
def: A large or excessive amount of something.

etym: Late 17th century: from Latin effervescent- boiling up, from the verb effervescere (see effervesce.
def: Bubbles in a liquid; fizz.

etym: Mid 17th century: from Greek oxumoron, neuter (used as a noun) of oxumoros pointedly foolish, from oxus sharp + moros foolish.
def: A figure of speech in which apparently contradictory terms appear in conjunction (e.g. faith unfaithful kept him falsely true ).

etym: Late 16th century: from French, or from Italian parapetto chest-high wall, from para- protecting + petto chest (from Latin pectus ).
def: A low protective wall along the edge of a roof, bridge, or balcony (balustrade).

etym: Mid 18th century: Italian, literally in the fresh (air).
def: In the open air.

etym: Late Middle English: via late Latin from Greek phulakterion amulet, from phulassein to guard.
def: A small leather box containing Hebrew texts on vellum, worn by Jewish men at morning prayer as a reminder to keep the law.

etym: Late 19th century: from German kaputt, from French (etre) capot (be) without tricks in a card game; compare with capot.
def: Broken and useless; no longer working or effective (capot).

etym: Mid 18th century (denoting something designed to elicit applause): from clap.
def: Absurd or nonsensical talk or ideas (clap).

etym: Early 20th century: the name of a musician in George du Maurier's novel Trilby (1894), who controls Trilby's stage singing hypnotically.
def: A person who exercises a controlling or mesmeric influence on another, especially for a sinister purpose.

etym: Mid 18th century: of unknown origin; perhaps a blend of Anglo-Irish cant auction and rancorous (see rancour.
def: Bad-tempered, argumentative, and uncooperative (bad-tempered).

etym: Mid 19th century: from Latin avunculus maternal uncle, diminutive of avus grandfather.
def: Kind and friendly towards a younger or less experienced person.

etym: Late 19th century: perhaps from Hooligan, the surname of a fictional rowdy Irish family in a music-hall song of the 1890s, also of a cartoon character.
def: A violent young troublemaker, typically one of a gang (hoodlum).

etym: Early 19th century: from Latin, from candela (see candle.
def: A large branched candlestick or holder for several candles or lamps (candle).

etym: Early 19th century (originally of a person): probably the second element of mumbo jumbo.
def: A very large person or thing (mumbo jumbo).

etym: Mid 16th century (in the sense denouement): from Latin catastropha, from Greek katastrophe overturning, sudden turn, from kata- down + strophe turning (from strephein to turn).
def: An event causing great and usually sudden damage or suffering; a disaster (disaster).

etym: Late Middle English: early form of Bethlehem.
def: A scene of uproar and confusion (uproar).

etym: Late 16th century: perhaps from Dutch boomken little tree or Middle Dutch bommekijn little barrel, used to denote a dumpy person.
def: An unsophisticated or socially awkward person from the countryside (yokel).

etym: Named after Gorgonzola, a village in northern Italy, where it was originally made.
def: A type of rich, strong-flavoured Italian cheese with bluish-green veins.

etym: Italian, literally detached.
def: With each sound or note sharply detached or separated from the others.

etym: Late Middle English: via Latin from Greek paidagogos, denoting a slave who accompanied a child to school (from pais, paid- boy + agogos guide).
def: A teacher, especially a strict or pedantic one.

etym: Early 20th century: probably of African origin; compare with Gullah moco witchcraft.
def: A magic charm, talisman, or spell.

etym: Old English utlendisc not native, from utland foreign country.
def: Looking or sounding bizarre or unfamiliar (weird).

etym: Mid 19th century (originally buncombe ): named after Buncombe County in North Carolina, mentioned in an inconsequential speech made by its congressman solely to please his constituents ( c.  1820).
def: Nonsense.

etym: Mid 19th century: alteration of Scots sculduddery, of unknown origin.
def: Underhand, unscrupulous, or dishonest behaviour or activities (trickery).

etym: Mid 16th century: from a-.
def: Not friendly or forthcoming; cool and distant (distant).

etym: Mid 17th century: from blather.
def: A person who talks at great length without making much sense (blather).

etym: 1920s (originally US): from dialect fainaigue cheat; perhaps from Old French fornier deny.
def: Obtain by dishonest or devious means.

etym: Middle English headling (from head.
def: With the head foremost (head first).

etym: Early 19th century: probably from Irish smidirin .
def: Small pieces.

etym: Mid 16th century: perhaps of Irish origin; compare with the Irish exclamations ababu, abu, used in battle cries.
def: A chaotic din caused by a crowd of people (noise).

etym: Mid 17th century: from Italian, literally unknown, from Latin incognitus, from in- not + cognitus (past participle of cognoscere know).
def: (of a person) having one's true identity concealed (unrecognized).

etym: Late Middle English (in .
def: A material prepared in ancient Egypt from the pithy stem of a water plant, used in sheets throughout the ancient Mediterranean world for writing or painting on and also for making articles such as rope.

etym: Middle English: from Old French sojourner, based on Latin sub- under + late Latin diurnum day.
def: A temporary stay (stay).

etym: Mid 17th century: from French hippogriffe, from Italian ippogrifo, from Greek hippos horse + Italian grifo griffin.
def: A mythical creature with the body of a horse and the wings and head of an eagle, born of the union of a male griffin and a filly.

etym: Mid 16th century: from Greek misanthropos, from misein to hate + anthropos man.
def: A person who dislikes humankind and avoids human society (cynic).

etym: Late 16th century: from Spanish contrabanda, from Italian contrabando, from contra- against + bando proclamation, ban.
def: Goods that have been imported or exported illegally (bootleg).

etym: Early 17th century (denoting a dish made with oatmeal or wheatmeal boiled to a jelly): from Welsh llymru ; perhaps related to llymrig soft, slippery.
def: Meaningless or insincere flattery or conventions.

etym: Mid 18th century: reduplication of hallo, hullo, etc.
def: A commotion; a fuss (fuss).

etym: Late Middle English: from French, from Latin murmuratio(n- ), from murmurare to murmur. The usage as a collective noun dates from the late 15th century.
def: The action of murmuring.

etym: Mid 17th century: probably via Portuguese lingoa from Latin lingua tongue.
def: A foreign language or local dialect.

etym: Late 19th century: from Spanish, insane.
def: A locomotive.

etym: Late Middle English: from ecclesiastical Latin pusillanimis (translating Greek olugopsukhos ), from pusillus very small + animus mind, + -ous.
def: Showing a lack of courage or determination; timid (-ous).

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin fortuitus, from forte by chance, from fors chance, luck.
def: Happening by chance rather than intention (chance).

etym: Late 16th century (as the endorsement made by a grand jury on an indictment considered backed by insufficient evidence to bring before a petty jury): Latin, literally we do not know (in legal use we take no notice of it), from ignorare (see ignore.
def: An ignorant or stupid person (ignore).

etym: Late 15th century: from late Latin mellifluus (from mel honey + fluere to flow) + -ous.
def: (of a sound) pleasingly smooth and musical to hear (sweet-sounding).

etym: Early 17th century: from Anglo-Norman French floteson, from floter to float.
def: The wreckage of a ship or its cargo found floating on or washed up by the sea (wreckage).

etym: Late Middle English: via Old French from Latin magnificent- making great, based on magnus great.
def: Extremely beautiful, elaborate, or impressive (splendid).

etym: Late 19th century: perhaps related to ruction.
def: A row or commotion (ruction).

etym: Mid 17th century: from Dutch kaketoe, from Malay kakatua, the spelling influenced by cock.
def: A parrot with an erectile crest, found in Australia, eastern Indonesia, and neighbouring islands (cock).

etym: Early 17th century: via late Latin from Greek suzugia, from suzugos yoked, paired, from sun- with, together + the stem of zeugnunai to yoke.
def: A conjunction or opposition, especially of the moon with the sun.

etym: Late 18th century: perhaps related to diddle.
def: A petty lie (diddle).

etym: 1960s: Yiddish.
def: A small object that is decorative rather than strictly functional; a trinket.

etym: Mid 18th century: from Sioux tipi dwelling.
def: A conical tent made of skins, cloth, or canvas on a frame of poles, used by American Indians of the Plains and Great Lakes regions.

etym: Late 19th century: from tele-.
def: The supposed ability to move objects at a distance by mental power or other non-physical means (tele-).

etym: Mid 17th century (as tyd bit, tid-bit ): from dialect tid tender (of unknown origin) + bit.
def: A small piece of tasty food (delicacy).

etym: Mid 19th century: from Latin tintinnabulum tinkling bell (from tintinnare, reduplication of tinnire to ring, tinkle) + -ation.
def: A ringing or tinkling sound (-ation).

etym: Early 19th century: said to be a contraction of toad-eater, a charlatan's assistant who ate toads; toads were regarded as poisonous, and the assistant's survival was thought to be due to the efficacy of the charlatan's remedy.
def: A person who behaves obsequiously to someone important (sycophant).

etym: Early 16th century: a jingle apparently based on top.
def: Upside down (upside down).

etym: Early 18th century: from modern Latin trapezoides, from late Greek trapezoeides, from trapeza table (see trapezium.
def: A quadrilateral with no sides parallel (trapezium).

etym: Mid 16th century: from Old French tumultuous or Latin tumultuosus, from tumultus (see tumult.
def: Making an uproar or loud, confused noise (loud).

etym: Late 16th century: partly via Portuguese from Arabic tufan (perhaps from Greek tuphon whirlwind); reinforced by Chinese dialect tai fung big wind.
def: A tropical storm in the region of the Indian or western Pacific oceans (cyclone).

etym: Mid 19th century: from German Umlaut, from um about + Laut sound.
def: A mark ( ) used over a vowel, especially in German, to indicate a different vowel quality.

etym: Early 20th century: humorous formation based on -teen.
def: Indefinitely many; a lot of (-teen).

etym: Middle English (in the sense appropriate a right wrongfully): from Old French usurper, from Latin usurpare seize for use.
def: Take (a position of power or importance) illegally or by force (seize).

etym: Late Middle English: from late Latin, diminutive of Latin uva grape.
def: A fleshy extension at the back of the soft palate which hangs above the throat.

etym: Mid 19th century: from Spanish vamos let us go.
def: Depart hurriedly.

etym: Early 17th century: from Latin verisimilitudo, from verisimilis probable, from veri (genitive of verus true) + similis like.
def: The appearance of being true or real.

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin, whirling, from vertere to turn.
def: A sensation of whirling and loss of balance, associated particularly with looking down from a great height, or caused by disease affecting the inner ear or the vestibular nerve; giddiness (dizziness).

etym: Late 17th century (denoting special talent in writing): from French, vigour, earlier form of expression, from Latin verba words.
def: Vigour and spirit or enthusiasm (enthusiasm).

etym: Early 17th century: from Italian, literally 'learned, skilful', from late Latin virtuosus (see virtuous).
def: A person highly skilled in music or another artistic pursuit (genius).

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin vivax, vivac- lively, vigorous (from vivere to live) + -ious.
def: (especially of a woman) attractively lively and animated (lively).

etym: Perhaps from Zulu.
def: A long horn blown by fans at soccer matches in South Africa.

etym: 1990s: from wackadoo.
def: An eccentric or fanatical person (wackadoo).

etym: Early 20th century: from German Wanderlust .
def: A strong desire to travel.

etym: Late 17th century: perhaps representing whipsnapper, expressing noise and unimportance.
def: A young and inexperienced person considered to be presumptuous or overconfident (pipsqueak).

etym: Late Middle English: from whirl.
def: A toy that spins round, for example a top or windmill (roundabout).

etym: 1930s: from who done it?, non-standard form of who did it?.
def: A story or play about a murder in which the identity of the murderer is not revealed until the end.

etym: 1930s: perhaps an alteration of gadget.
def: A small gadget or mechanical device (gadget).

etym: Early 17th century: from Ojibwa wigwaum, Algonquian wikiwam their house.
def: A dome-shaped hut or tent made by fastening mats, skins, or bark over a framework of poles (as used formerly by some North American Indian peoples).

etym: Early 17th century: later spelling of will I, nill I I am willing, I am unwilling.
def: Whether one likes it or not (necessarily).

etym: Late 16th century: from Middle Dutch wijsseggher soothsayer, probably from the Germanic base of wit.
def: A person with an affectation of wisdom or knowledge, regarded with scorn or irritation by others; a know-all (wit).

etym: Early 20th century: from wise.
def: A person who behaves in an irritatingly smug or arrogant fashion, typically by making clever remarks and displaying their knowledge (wise).

etym: early 18th century: reduplication of washy.
def: (of drink or liquid food) weak; watery (watery).

etym: Middle English (in the sense afflicted with grief): from woe.
def: Sad or miserable in appearance (sad).

etym: Late 19th century: from German, from Wunder wonder + Kind child.
def: A person who achieves great success when relatively young.

etym: Mid 19th century: from xylo-.
def: A musical instrument played by striking a row of wooden bars of graduated length with one or more small wooden or plastic beaters (xylo-).

etym: Mid 18th century: from the name of an imaginary race of brutish creatures in Swift's Gulliver's Travels (1726).
def: A rude, noisy, or violent person (barbarian).

etym: Early 19th century: perhaps figuratively from dialect yokel green woodpecker.
def: An uneducated and unsophisticated person from the countryside (bumpkin).

etym: 1930s: Yiddish, from German saftig juicy.
def: (of a woman) having a full, rounded figure; plump.

etym: Mid 19th century: from German Zeitgeist, from Zeit time + Geist spirit.
def: The defining spirit or mood of a particular period of history as shown by the ideas and beliefs of the time.

etym: Late Old English zefferus, denoting a personification of the west wind, via Latin from Greek zephuros (god of the) west wind. Sense 1 dates from the late 17th century.
def: A soft gentle breeze.

etym: From Akkadian ziqqurratu .
def: (in ancient Mesopotamia) a rectangular stepped tower, sometimes surmounted by a temple. Ziggurats are first attested in the late 3rd millennium BC and probably inspired the biblical story of the Tower of Babel (Gen. 11:19).

etym: Early 18th century: from French, from German Zickzack, symbolic of alternation of direction, first applied to fortifications.
def: A line or course having abrupt alternate right and left turns (meandering).

etym: 1960s: Louisiana Creole, possibly from a pronunciation of French les haricots in a dance-tune title.
def: A kind of black American dance music originally from southern Louisiana, typically featuring accordion and guitar.

etym: Late 19th century: modern Latin, from Latin decumbere ‘lie down’, on the pattern of words such as accubitus ‘reclining at table’.
def: The posture adopted by a person who is lying down.
usage: ‘lumbar puncture with the patient in the lateral decubitus position’

etym: Early 17th century: probably an alteration of obsolete fadge ‘to fit’. Early usage was as a verb in the sense ‘turn out as expected’, also ‘merge together’: this probably gave rise to its use in confectionery. In the late 17th century the verb came to mean ‘fit together in a clumsy or underhand manner’, which included facts or figures being cobbled together in a superficially convincing way: this led to the exclamation ‘fudge!’ and to noun fudge (sense 3 of the noun).
def: A soft crumbly or chewy sweet made from sugar, butter, and milk or cream.
usage: ‘a sundae with whipped cream, ice cream, hot fudge, and a cherry on top’

etym:
Mid 17th century (as a noun): from modern Latin, neuter (used as a noun)
 of the Latin adjective maximus, superlative of magnus ‘great’. The 
adjectival use dates from the early 19th century.
def: A maximum amount or setting.
usage: ‘the sound is distorted to the max’

etym: Portuguese.
def: (especially with reference to songs or poetry) a feeling of longing, melancholy, or nostalgia that is supposedly characteristic of the Portuguese or Brazilian temperament.
usage: ‘her songs are based on love poems and evoke a melancholy known to the Portuguese as saudade’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin pulchritudo, from pulcher, pulchr- ‘beautiful’.
def: Beauty.
usage: ‘the irresistible pulchritude of her friend’

etym: Late 17th century: perhaps of Cornish origin.
def: Drink alcohol to excess, especially on a regular basis.
usage: ‘he was toping the while from a flagon of sack’

etym: Late Middle English (denoting a doorkeeper): from Anglo-Norman French usser, from medieval Latin ustiarius, from Latin ostiarius, from ostium ‘door’.
def: A person who shows people to their seats, especially in a cinema or theatre or at a wedding.
usage: ‘a waiter ushered me to a table’

etym: Old English manigfeald; current noun senses date from the mid 19th century.
def: Many and various.
usage: ‘the implications of this decision were manifold’

etym: Early 17th century: Latin.
def: For each year (used in financial contexts)
usage: ‘an average growth rate of 2 per cent per annum’

etym: Late Middle English: of unknown origin.
def: A hard, typically green stone used for ornaments and implements and consisting of the minerals jadeite or nephrite.
usage: ‘a jade figurine’

etym: Latin, literally ‘of fact’.
def: In fact, whether by right or not.
usage: ‘the country was de facto divided between two states’

etym: Latin, literally ‘be well!, be strong!’, imperative of valere.
def: A valley (used in place names or as a poetic term)
usage: ‘the Vale of Glamorgan’

etym: Latin, literally ‘of law’.
def: According to rightful entitlement or claim; by right.
usage: ‘the resolution declared that the independent Republic of Latvia proclaimed on November 18, 1918 was still in existence de jure’

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin perfidiosus, from perfidia ‘treachery’.
def: Deceitful and untrustworthy.
usage: ‘a perfidious lover’

etym: Middle English: from be- (as an intensifier) + obsolete tide ‘befall’, from Old English tīdan ‘happen’, from tīd (see tide).
def: Happen.
usage: ‘I waited with beating heart, not knowing what would betide’

etym: Mid 16th century: from French, from Italian cannonata, from cannone (see cannon).
def: A period of continuous heavy gunfire.
usage: ‘the French attack began with a cannonade’

etym: From Middle English waccheword, morphologically as watch +‎ word.
def: A word or phrase expressing a person's or group's core aim or belief.
usage: ‘on all educational fronts, innovation was the watchword’

etym: Old English sār (noun and adjective), sāre (adverb), of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zeer ‘sore’ and German sehr ‘very’. The original sense was ‘causing intense pain, grievous’, whence the adverbial use.
def: (of a part of one's body) painful or aching.
usage: ‘she had a sore throat’

etym: Mid 18th century: perhaps from Spanish bojar ‘sail round’, from Middle Low German bōgen ‘bend’, from the base of bow.
def: A container with a flat base and sides, typically square or rectangular and having a lid.
usage: ‘a cigarette box’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘make known’): from Old French descovrir, from late Latin discooperire, from Latin dis- (expressing reversal) + cooperire ‘cover completely’ (see cover).
def: Find unexpectedly or during a search.
usage: ‘firemen discovered a body in the debris’

etym: Middle English: via Old French from medieval Latin trepalium ‘instrument of torture’, from Latin tres ‘three’ + palus ‘stake’.
def: Painful or laborious effort.
usage: ‘advice for those who wish to save great sorrow and travail’

etym: Latin.
def: Among other things.
usage: ‘the study includes, inter alia, computers, aircraft, and pharmaceuticals’

etym: Late Middle English: from French scrupule or Latin scrupulus, from scrupus, literally ‘rough pebble’, (figuratively) ‘anxiety’.
def: A feeling of doubt or hesitation with regard to the morality or propriety of a course of action.
usage: ‘I had no scruples about eavesdropping’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French espousaille, from Latin sponsalia ‘betrothal’, neuter plural of sponsalis (adjective), from sponsare ‘espouse, betroth’ (see espouse).
def: An act of adopting or supporting a cause, belief, or way of life.
usage: ‘his espousal of Western ideas’

etym: From Urdu ustād.
def: An expert or highly skilled person, especially a musician.
usage: ‘Ustad Zakir Hussain’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘having a certain status by birth’): from Old French, from Latin naturalis, from natura ‘birth, nature, quality’ (see nature).
def: Existing in or derived from nature; not made or caused by humankind.
usage: ‘carrots contain a natural antiseptic’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘pail, small cask’): from Old Norse staup, of Germanic origin; related to the verb steep.
def: A basin for holy water, especially on the wall near the door of a Roman Catholic church for worshippers to dip their fingers in before crossing themselves.
usage: ‘the jailer returned and left a stoup of water’

etym: Middle English: from Old French pal, from Latin palus ‘stake’.
def: Light in colour or shade; containing little colour or pigment.
usage: ‘choose pale floral patterns for walls’

etym:
"female servant," c. 1300, 
from hand (n.) in the sense in close at hand + maid. Compare Old English
 handþegn "personal attendant" and the original sense of handsome.
def: A female servant.
usage: ‘this is not to say that the researcher simply becomes the handmaid of the practitioner’

etym: French.
def: For want of a better alternative.
usage: ‘women often couldn't pay the fines, and sheriffs could end up imprisoning them faute de mieux’

etym: Late 18th century: French, past participle of manquer ‘to lack’.
def: Having failed to become what one might have been.
usage: ‘he was a creature of suppressed passions, an artist manqué’

etym: Late 15th century: from Latin refulgent- ‘shining out’, from the verb refulgere, from re- (expressing intensive force) + fulgere ‘to shine’.
def: Shining very brightly.
usage: ‘refulgent blue eyes’

etym: Old English lettan ‘hinder’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch letten, also to late.
def: Not prevent or forbid; allow.
usage: ‘my boss let me leave early’

etym: Mid 16th century (as a noun denoting an inhabitant of the woods): from French sylvain or Latin Silvanus ‘woodland deity’, from silva ‘a wood’.
def: Consisting of or associated with woods; wooded.
usage: ‘a sylvan glade’

etym: Old English stillice; see still (adj.) + -ly.
def: Quietly and with little movement.
usage: ‘the birds rested stilly’

etym: Middle English: from Old French oncle, from late Latin aunculus, alteration of Latin avunculus ‘maternal uncle’ (see avuncular).
def: The brother of one's father or mother or the husband of one's aunt.
usage: ‘he visited his uncle’

etym: Late Middle English (in the sense ‘illuminate a manuscript’): alteration of obsolete lumine ‘illuminate’, via Old French luminer from Latin luminare ‘make light’.
def: Depict or describe in painting or words.
usage: ‘Miss Read limns a gentler world in her novels’

etym: "dawn of the day," mid-15c., from cock (n.1) + crow (v.). An Old English word on a similar notion was hanered.
def: Dawn.
usage: ‘she helped him to dance until cockcrow’

etym: Mid 16th century: from Latin, literally ‘the people's voice’.
def: The opinions or beliefs of the majority.
usage: ‘her poems weren't exactly the vox populi’

etym: Old English behōf, of West Germanic origin; related to Dutch behoef and German Behuf, also to heave.
def: Benefit or advantage.
usage: ‘to make laws for the behoof of the colony’

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin sesquipedalis ‘a foot and a half long’, from sesqui- (see sesqui-) + pes, ped- ‘foot’.
def: (of a word) polysyllabic; long.
usage: ‘sesquipedalian surnames’

etym: First recorded in 1400–50, lightsome is from the late Middle English word lyghtesum. See light, -some.
def: Happy and carefree.
usage: ‘lightsome, high-flying dancers’

etym: Old English hwider, from the Germanic base of which; compare with hither and thither.
def: To what place or state.
usage: ‘whither are we bound?’

etym: Old English gemǣd(e)d  ‘maddened’, participial form related to gemād  ‘mad’, of Germanic origin.
def: Acting madly; frenzied.
usage: ‘observe the madding motion of his eyes’

etym: French, literally ‘stroke of hand’.
def: A sudden surprise attack, especially one made by an army during war.
usage: ‘the bridge was seized by a coup de main’

etym: Early 16th century: from obsolete dote ‘folly’ + -ish.
def: Stupid or silly.
usage: ‘dotish foreign TV programmes’

etym: French, literally ‘as is necessary’.
def: Correct in behaviour or etiquette.
usage: ‘my friend is partial to cocaine—in every other way he is very proper and comme il faut’

etym: Middle English: from very + -ly, suggested by Old French verrai(e)ment.
def: Truly; certainly.
usage: ‘verily these men are mad’

etym: From Middle English therwith, from Old English þǣrwiþ (“therewith, in return, in exchange, against”), equivalent to there +‎ with. Cognate with Danish derved (“therewith”), Swedish därvid (“therewith, thereby”). Parallel with Dutch daarmee, German damit (“therewith”), though etymologically different.
def: With or in the thing mentioned.
usage: ‘documents lodged therewith’

etym: Old English bōtlēas ‘not able to be compensated for by payment’ (see boot, -less).
def: (of a task or undertaking) ineffectual; useless.
usage: ‘remonstrating with him seems ever to have been a bootless task’

etym: 1920s (originally US): imitative.
def: Destroy or obliterate.
usage: ‘zap the enemy's artillery before it can damage your core units’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French.
def: (in French cooking) a small, flowerpot-shaped mould in which an individual sweet or savoury dish is cooked and served.
usage: ‘set the filled darioles in the saucepan’

etym: Early 17th century: from French déterger or Latin detergere ‘wipe away’.
def: Cleanse thoroughly.
usage: ‘she wanted to deterge herself completely of it’

etym: Middle English: from Old French relever, from Latin relevare, from re- (expressing intensive force) + levare ‘raise’ (from levis ‘light’).
def: Cause (pain, distress, or difficulty) to become less severe or serious.
usage: ‘the drug was used to promote sleep and to relieve pain’

etym: Latin.
def: In the original place.
usage: ‘frescoes have been left in situ’

etym: Mid 19th century: from German Zeitgeist, from Zeit ‘time’ + Geist ‘spirit’.
def: The defining spirit or mood of a particular period of history as shown by the ideas and beliefs of the time.
usage: ‘the story captured the zeitgeist of the late 1960s’

etym: From green +‎ sward.
def: Grass-covered ground.
usage: ‘city workers lolling on the greensward’

etym: Latin.
def: By that very fact or act.
usage: ‘the enemy of one's enemy may be ipso facto a friend’

etym: Late 18th century: French, ‘in a mass’.
def: In a group; all together.
usage: ‘the cabinet immediately resigned en masse’

etym: Mid 19th century: French, from cordon ‘line, border’ (see cordon) + sanitaire ‘sanitary’.
def: A guarded line preventing anyone from leaving an area infected by a disease and thus spreading it.
usage: ‘inoculations replaced cordons sanitaires as a major medical intervention’

etym: Mid 18th century: French, literally ‘excessive’.
def: Not wanted; unwelcome.
usage: ‘she had no grasp of the conversation and felt herself de trop’

etym: 520s, from fish (n.) + wife (n.) in the "woman" sense. Also fish-fag.
def: A coarse-mannered woman who is prone to shouting.
usage: ‘the screech of a fishwife’

etym: Late 16th century (in the sense ‘power of hearing or listening’): from Latin auditio(n-), from audire ‘hear’. Sense 1 of the noun dates from the late 19th century.
def: An interview for a role or job as a singer, actor, dancer, or musician, consisting of a practical demonstration of the candidate's suitability and skill.
usage: ‘the Royal Ballet gave Nicola an audition’

etym: Middle English: from Old French compas (noun), compasser (verb), based on Latin com- ‘together’ + passus ‘a step or pace’. Several senses (‘measure’, ‘artifice’, ‘circumscribed area’, and ‘pair of compasses’) which appeared in Middle English are also found in Old French, but their development and origin are uncertain. The transference of sense to the magnetic compass is held to have occurred in the related Italian word compasso, from the circular shape of the compass box.
def: An instrument containing a magnetized pointer which shows the direction of magnetic north and bearings from it.
