etym: Late 16th century: from Latin divagat- ‘wandered about’, from the verb divagari, from di- ‘widely’ + vagari ‘wander’.
def: Stray or digress.
usage: ‘Yeats divagated into Virgil's territory only once’

etym: French, literally ‘joy of living’.
def: Exuberant enjoyment of life.
usage: ‘they seem to be filled with joie de vivre’

etym: French, from Old French paste ‘pie of seasoned meat’.
def: A person's head.
usage: ‘he scratched his balding pate’

etym: Welsh.
def: (in Welsh use) a stirring feeling of emotional motivation and energy.
usage: ‘the hwyl is back in London Welsh’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French a pas ‘at (a considerable) pace’.
def: Swiftly; quickly.
usage: ‘work continues apace’

etym: Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French cordewaner, from Old French cordewan, ‘of Cordoba’ (see cordovan).
def: A shoemaker (still used in the names of guilds)
usage: ‘the Cordwainers' Company’

etym: Mid 18th century: from French caducité, from caduc, from Latin caducus ‘liable to fall’, from cadere ‘to fall’.
def: The infirmity of old age; senility.
usage: ‘my father was attacked with symptoms of caducity’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French vexer, from Latin vexare ‘shake, disturb’.
def: Make (someone) feel annoyed, frustrated, or worried, especially with trivial matters.
usage: ‘the memory of the conversation still vexed him’

etym: Latin.
def: In his or her own person.
usage: ‘many people find him, both in his verse and in propria persona, too loud and pushy’

etym: Late 15th century: from Old French plaissier, based on Latin plectere ‘to plait’. Compare with pleach.
def: A splashing sound.
usage: ‘the plash of the fountain’

etym: 1540s, 'not possessed in common,' from un- (1) 'not' + common (adj.). Meaning 'not commonly occurring, unusual, rare' is recorded from 1610s. Related: Uncommonly.
def: Out of the ordinary; unusual.
usage: ‘prostate cancer is not uncommon in men over 60’

etym: Old English, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch vos and German Fuchs.
def: A carnivorous mammal of the dog family with a pointed muzzle and bushy tail, proverbial for its cunning.
usage: ‘a wily old fox’

etym: Late 17th century: from Pantagruel (the name of an enormous giant in Rabelais's novel Pantagruel (1532)) + -ian.
def: Enormous.
usage: ‘a Pantagruelian banquet’

etym: French, literally ‘feat of strength’.
def: A performance or achievement that has been accomplished or managed with great skill.
usage: ‘his novel is a tour de force’

etym: Middle English: via Old French from Latin fervent- ‘boiling’, from the verb fervere. Compare with fervid and fervour.
def: Having or displaying a passionate intensity.
usage: ‘a fervent supporter of the revolution’

etym: Middle English: from Old French, from Latin fructus ‘enjoyment of produce, harvest’, from frui ‘enjoy’, related to fruges ‘fruits of the earth’, plural (and most common form) of frux, frug- ‘fruit’.
def: The sweet and fleshy product of a tree or other plant that contains seed and can be eaten as food.
usage: ‘tropical fruits such as mangoes and papaya’

etym: 1980s: shortened from vocals, probably after Latin vox ‘voice’.
def: (especially in music journalism) vocals; voice.
usage: ‘his matinee-idol vox’

etym: French, literally ‘grand lady’.
def: A woman holding an influential position within a particular sphere.
usage: ‘the grande dame of British sculpture’

etym: French, literally ‘high world’.
def: Fashionable society.
usage: ‘the haut monde's artificial hypocrisy’

etym: Late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French receite, from medieval Latin recepta ‘received’, feminine past participle of Latin recipere. The -p- was inserted in imitation of the Latin spelling.
def: The action of receiving something or the fact of its being received.
usage: ‘I would be grateful if you would acknowledge receipt of this letter’

etym: Early 16th century (denoting a small swirling stream): probably imitative; compare with Norwegian purla ‘bubble up’.
def: Denoting or relating to a knitting stitch made by putting the needle through the front of the stitch from right to left.
usage: ‘knit one, purl one’

etym: Old English tēotha (adjective in the ordinal sense ‘tenth’, used in a specialized sense as a noun), tēothian (verb).
def: One tenth of annual produce or earnings, formerly taken as a tax for the support of the Church and clergy.
usage: ‘he hadn't said a tithe of the prayers he knew’

etym: Middle English: from Old French repairer, from late Latin repatriare ‘return to one's country’ (see repatriate).
def: Restore (something damaged, faulty, or worn) to a good condition.
usage: ‘faulty electrical appliances should be repaired by an electrician’

etym: French, literally ‘by excellence’.
def: Better or more than all others of the same kind.
usage: ‘Nash is, to many, the Regency architect par excellence’

etym: Mid 17th century: from late Latin constellatus, from con- ‘together’ + stellatus ‘arranged like a star’.
def: Form or cause to form into a cluster or group; gather together.
usage: ‘the towns and valleys where people constellate’

etym: Middle English: from Old French condicion (noun), condicionner (verb), from Latin condicio(n-) ‘agreement’, from condicere ‘agree upon’, from con- ‘with’ + dicere ‘say’.
def: The state of something with regard to its appearance, quality, or working order.
usage: ‘the wiring is in good condition’

etym: Also forefend, late 14c., 'to protect; to prohibit; to avert, fend off, prevent,' a hybrid from for- + fend 'to ward off.' Archaic, if not obsolete.
def: Avert or prevent (something evil or unpleasant)
usage: ‘‘The fiend forfend’ said the grim Earl’

etym: Middle English: alteration of Scots and northern English sloom, in the same sense. The -b- was added for ease of pronunciation.
def: Sleep.
usage: ‘Sleeping Beauty slumbered in her forest castle’

etym: Old English spēd (noun), spēdan (verb), from the Germanic base of Old English spōwan ‘prosper, succeed’, a sense reflected in early usage.
def: The rate at which someone or something moves or operates or is able to move or operate.
usage: ‘we turned on to the runway and began to gather speed’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French, from a ‘to’ + Dieu ‘God’; compare with adios.
def: Goodbye.
usage: ‘he whispered a fond adieu’

etym: French, from soi ‘oneself’ + disant ‘saying’.
def: Self-styled; so-called.
usage: ‘a soi-disant novelist’

etym: Middle English: from Old French dameisele, damisele, based on Latin domina ‘mistress’.
def: A young unmarried woman.
usage: ‘she makes a rather sweet damsel in distress’

etym: Middle English: via Old French from Latin visus ‘sight’, from videre ‘to see’.
def: A person's face, with reference to the form or proportions of the features.
usage: ‘an elegant, angular visage’

etym: Early 19th century: from Latin plangent- ‘lamenting’, from the verb plangere.
def: (of a sound) loud and resonant, with a mournful tone.
usage: ‘the plangent sound of a harpsichord’

etym: From jungle + the suffix -i (as in Hindi); compare with Hindi janglī.
def: Uncultured; wild.
usage: ‘they are jungli, not educated people’

etym: French, literally ‘terrible child’.
def: A person who behaves in an unconventional or controversial way.
usage: ‘the enfant terrible of contemporary art’

etym: Mid 19th century: from German, literally ‘double-goer’.
def: An apparition or double of a living person.
usage: ‘he has been replaced by an evil doppelgänger’

etym: Mid 16th century (in freak (sense 4 of the noun)): probably from a dialect word.
def: A very unusual and unexpected event or situation.
usage: ‘the teacher says the accident was a total freak’

etym: Middle English: from Old French per (or par) auenture ‘by chance’.
def: Perhaps.
usage: ‘peradventure I'm not as wealthy as he is’

etym: 1970s: from Greek emetikos ‘vomiting’, from emein ‘to vomit’ + -phobia.
def: Extreme fear of vomiting.
usage: ‘she first remembers experiencing emetophobia at boarding school at the age of six’

etym: Middle English endite, from Old French enditier, based on Latin indicere (see indict).
def: Write; compose.
usage: ‘he indites the wondrous tale of Our Lord’

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin ingurgitat- ‘poured in, drenched’, from the verb ingurgitare, from in- ‘into’ + gurges, gurgit- ‘whirlpool, gulf’.
def: Swallow (something) greedily.
usage: ‘its empty holds are ingurgitating a vast, continuous rush of murky brown seawater’

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin praevis- ‘foreseen, anticipated’, from the verb praevidere, from prae ‘before’ + videre ‘to see’.
def: Foresee or predict (an event)
usage: ‘he had intelligence to previse the possible future’

etym: From Afar qafar.
def: At or to a distance.
usage: ‘for months he had loved her from afar’

etym: Mid 19th century: of unknown origin.
def: Spend time aimlessly; idle.
usage: ‘she goes to Arizona every January to lollygag in the sun’

etym: Late 16th century: from French embuscade, from Italian imboscata, Spanish emboscada, or Portuguese embuscada, based on a late Latin word meaning ‘to place in a wood’; related to bush.
def: An ambush.
usage: ‘our sensibilities are being battered with reports of killings and ambuscades’

etym: 1650s, 'jailer,' from turn (v.) + key (n.). In reference to a job that only has to be done only once, it is recorded from 1934. The notion probably is of something that can be accomplished with a single turn of a key.
def: A jailer.
usage: ‘turnkey systems for telecommunications customers’

etym: Early 19th century: French, literally ‘know how to do’.
def: The ability to act or speak appropriately in social situations.
usage: ‘this is a gracious occasion, so try to behave with a bit of savoir faire’

etym: Middle English wæs hæil ‘be in (good) health!’: from Old Norse ves heill (compare with hail). The drinking formula wassail (and the reply drinkhail ‘drink good health’) were probably introduced by Danish-speaking inhabitants of England, and then spread, so that by the 12th century the usage was considered by the Normans to be characteristic of Englishmen.
def: Spiced ale or mulled wine drunk during celebrations for Twelfth Night and Christmas Eve.
usage: ‘a mighty bowl of wassail in which the apples were hissing and bubbling’

etym: 'capacity for yielding to pressure,' 1868, from give (v.). The Middle English noun yeve, meant 'that which is given or offered; a contribution of money,' often as tribute, or in expectation of something in return.
def: A fetter or shackle.
usage: ‘Thomas Chase lay bound most painfully with chains, gyves, manacles, and irons’

etym: Old English hider, of Germanic origin; related to he and here.
def: To or towards this place.
usage: ‘I little knew then that such calamity would summon me hither!’

etym: Old English gecleopod, past participle of cleopian ‘call’, of Germanic origin.
def: By the name of.
usage: ‘a lady yclept Eleanora’

etym: Mid-15c., contraction of it is.
def: It is.
usage: ‘‘'tis but a scratch,’ she murmured’

etym: Old English brand ‘burning’ (also in brand (sense 3 of the noun)), of Germanic origin; related to German Brand, also to burn. The verb sense ‘mark with a hot iron’ dates from late Middle English, giving rise to the noun sense ‘a mark of ownership made by branding’ (mid 17th century), whence brand (sense 1 of the noun) (early 19th century).
def: A type of product manufactured by a particular company under a particular name.
usage: ‘a new brand of soap powder’

etym: French, literally ‘in the natural (state)’.
def: With no elaborate treatment, dressing, or preparation.
usage: ‘the cheese is delicious whether au naturel or seasoned’

etym: Middle English: from medieval Latin clario(n-), from Latin clarus ‘clear’.
def: A shrill narrow-tubed war trumpet.
usage: ‘clarion trumpeters’

etym: Mid 16th century: from Old French ensorceler, alteration of ensorcerer, from sorcier ‘sorcerer’.
def: Enchant; fascinate.
usage: ‘he was a child when the power of a mythic image first ensorcelled him’

etym: Middle English: from Latin corruptus, past participle of corrumpere ‘mar, bribe, destroy’, from cor- ‘altogether’ + rumpere ‘to break’.
def: Having or showing a willingness to act dishonestly in return for money or personal gain.
usage: ‘unscrupulous logging companies assisted by corrupt officials’

etym: Middle English (as a noun): probably from Old Norse skáld ‘skald’.
def: Remonstrate with or rebuke (someone) angrily.
usage: ‘Mum took Anna away, scolding her for her bad behaviour’

etym: Late Old English, from Old Norse skot ‘a shot’, reinforced by Old French escot, of Germanic origin; related to shot.
def: (in the UK) Football Association, the governing body of soccer in England.
usage: ‘the FA Premier League’

etym: Early 17th century: from the verb poll + -ard.
def: Cut off the top and branches of (a tree) to encourage new growth at the top.
usage: ‘a wide boulevard lined with pollarded lime trees’

etym: Late Middle English: from Scots fank ‘coil of rope’ + -le.
def: Entangle.
usage: ‘the tape got fankled in the motorbike's front wheels’

etym: Late 16th century: via Latin from Greek philippikos, the name given to Demosthenes' speeches against Philip II of Macedon, also to those of Cicero against Mark Antony.
def: A bitter attack or denunciation, especially a verbal one.
usage: ‘the lecture was a tremendous philippic against our culture’

etym: Latin, literally ‘way of operating’.
def: A particular way or method of doing something.
usage: ‘every killer has his own special modus operandi’

etym: Middle English: from Old French venerie, from vener ‘to hunt’, from Latin venari.
def: Sexual indulgence.
usage: ‘not a few of them engaged in venery’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘faithful, trusty’): from Old Norse tryggr; related to true. The current verb sense dates from the late 17th century.
def: Trigonometry.
usage: ‘two trig little boys, each in a gray flannel suit’

etym: Middle English: via Old French from Latin firmamentum, from firmare ‘fix, settle’.
def: The heavens or sky.
usage: ‘thunder shakes the firmament’

etym: 'thief,' 1803, from larceny + -ist. Earlier was larcener (1630s).
def: A thief.
usage: ‘a nervous larcener with a sharp blade’

etym: Mid 18th century: from French, literally ‘to the fact, to the point’.
def: Having a good or detailed knowledge of.
usage: ‘you should be au fait with the company and its products’

etym: French, literally ‘high dressmaking’.
def: Expensive, fashionable clothes produced by leading fashion houses.
usage: ‘rails of haute couture’

etym: Latin, from ex ‘out of, from’ + officium ‘duty’.
def: By virtue of one's position or status.
usage: ‘an ex officio member of the committee’

etym: Latin, literally ‘under the rose’, as an emblem of secrecy.
def: Happening or done in secret.
usage: ‘the committee operates sub rosa’

etym: Early 17th century: perhaps from soil.
def: The upper layer of earth in which plants grow, a black or dark brown material typically consisting of a mixture of organic remains, clay, and rock particles.
usage: ‘blueberries need very acid soil’

etym: Latin, literally ‘to infinity’.
def: Again and again in the same way; forever.
usage: ‘registration is for seven years and may be renewed ad infinitum’

etym: Greek.
def: The fourteenth letter of the Greek alphabet (Ξ, ξ), transliterated as ‘x’.
usage: ‘Xi Cygni’

etym: Early 19th century: reduplication of dialect argle, a late 16th-century alteration of argue.
def: Copious but meaningless talk or writing; waffle.
usage: ‘bureaucratic argle-bargle’

etym: Old English innlīce (see in, -ly).
def: Inwardly.
usage: ‘inly stung with anger and disdain’

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin fugax, fugac- (from fugere ‘flee’) + -ious.
def: Tending to disappear; fleeting.
usage: ‘she was acutely conscious of her fugacious youth’

etym: Old English siex, six, syx, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch zes and German sechs, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin sex and Greek hex.
def: Equivalent to the product of two and three; one more than five, or four less than ten; 6.
usage: ‘she's lived here six months’

etym: Early 17th century: from late Latin inspissat- ‘made thick’, from the verb inspissare (based on Latin spissus ‘thick, dense’).
def: Thicken or congeal.
usage: ‘inspissated secretions’

etym: Late 16th century: from Latin obnubilat- ‘covered with clouds or fog’, from the verb obnubilare.
def: Darken or cover with or as if with a cloud; obscure.
usage: ‘never to be short of illusions, to obnubilate himself: such was his dream’

etym: 1930s: pluralized abbreviation.
def: Pictures, especially photographs.
usage: ‘a book of song lyrics and intimate pix’

etym: Late 17th century: French, literally ‘head-to-head’.
def: A private conversation between two people.
usage: ‘it so happened that their tête-à-tête was in earshot’

etym: Old English wiht ‘thing, creature’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch wicht ‘little child’ and German Wicht ‘creature’.
def: A person of a specified kind.
usage: ‘he always was an unlucky wight’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French, from Latin potatio(n-), from potare ‘to drink’.
def: An alcoholic drink.
usage: ‘lite potations are very American’

etym: Middle English: from Old French, based on Latin vestire ‘clothe’.
def: Clothing; dress.
usage: ‘a man garbed in ancient vesture’

etym: Early 17th century: from medieval Latin velleitas, from Latin velle ‘to wish’.
def: A wish or inclination not strong enough to lead to action.
usage: ‘the notion intrigued me, but remained a velleity’

etym: 1950s: of obscure origin.
def: (of a person) dishonest or suspect.
usage: ‘he knew the guy was hinky’

etym: Old English blōwan, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch bloeien and German blühen, also to bloom and blossom.
def: (of wind) move creating an air current.
usage: ‘a cold breeze was blowing in off the sea’

etym: Late Middle English (in the sense ‘booty, pilfered property’): from a variant of Old French pelfre ‘spoils’, of unknown origin. Compare with pilfer.
def: Money, especially when gained in a dishonest or dishonourable way.
usage: ‘damnation dog thee and thy wretched pelf!’

etym: Middle English (also denoting something morally corrupting): from Old French, from Latin pestilentia, based on pestis ‘a plague’.
def: A fatal epidemic disease, especially bubonic plague.
usage: ‘neither prayers nor demonstrations halted the advance of the pestilence’

etym: Mid 16th century: of Scandinavian origin, probably based on Old Norse kenna ‘know, perceive’ and spak-, spek- ‘wise or wisdom’.
def: Easily recognizable; conspicuous.
usage: ‘he loved walking in the village, where he was a kenspeckle figure’

etym: Middle English: from a- ‘on’ + broad.
def: In or to a foreign country or countries.
usage: ‘we usually go abroad for a week in May’

etym: Latin, literally ‘without a day’.
def: (with reference to business or proceedings that have been adjourned) with no appointed date for resumption.
usage: ‘the case was adjourned sine die’

etym: Late Middle English (as an adjective): via medieval Latin from Greek empurios, from en- ‘in’ + pur ‘fire’. The noun dates from the mid 17th century.
def: Relating to heaven or the sky.
usage: ‘the empyrean domain where human will and God's will became as one’

etym: Late Middle English: from Old French desporter, from des- ‘away’ + porter ‘carry’ (from Latin portare).
def: Enjoy oneself unrestrainedly; frolic.
usage: ‘a painting of ladies disporting themselves by a lake’

etym: Mid-15c., 'to set up, fix,' from up (adv.) + set (v.). Similar formation in Middle Dutch opsetten 'set up, propose,' German aufsetzen. Modern sense of 'overturn, capsize' (1803) is that of obsolete overset. In reference to the stomach, from 1834. Meaning 'to throw into mental discomposure' is from 1805. Related: Upsetting.
def: Overturn.
usage: ‘he overset the primus stove while cooking his supper’

etym: Latin, literally ‘to sickness’.
def: Used to refer to the fact that something has been done or repeated so often that it has become annoying or tiresome.
usage: ‘the phrase he repeated ad nauseam’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin fluxus, from fluere ‘to flow’.
def: The action or process of flowing or flowing out.
usage: ‘the flux of ions across the membrane’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin lucent- ‘shining’, from the verb lucere (see lucid).
def: Glowing with or giving off light.
usage: ‘the moon was lucent in the background’

etym: Early 17th century: from Spanish alcázar, from Arabic al-qaṣr ‘the castle’.
def: A Spanish palace or fortress of Moorish origin.
usage: ‘the gardens of the alcazar in Seville’

etym: 1970s: apparently an alteration of pass- (from passenger).
def: A call for a truce, used especially by schoolchildren when playing.
usage: ‘Pax! No offence meant, honest old chum’

etym: 1777, 'thing grabbed;' 1824, 'act of grabbing, a sudden grasp or seizing' from grab (v.). Up for grabs attested from 1945 in jive talk.
def: A length of cord or rope used for fastening or tying.
usage: ‘they prepared a great many seizings to tie the men with’

etym: Late Middle English: alteration of pocks, plural of pock.
def: Any of several viral diseases producing a rash of pimples that become pus-filled and leave pockmarks on healing.
usage: ‘a pox on both their houses!’

etym: Middle English: the noun from Old Norse vant, neuter of vanr ‘lacking’; the verb from Old Norse vanta ‘be lacking’. The original notion of ‘lack’ was early extended to ‘need’ and from this developed the sense ‘desire’.
def: Have a desire to possess or do (something); wish for.
usage: ‘I want an apple’

etym: Old English mē thyncth, from mē ‘to me’ + thyncth ‘it seems’ (from thyncan ‘seem’, related to think).
def: It seems to me.
usage: ‘life has been rather hard on her, methinks’

etym: Old English fægen ‘happy, well pleased’, of Germanic origin, from a base meaning ‘rejoice’; related to fawn.
def: Pleased or willing under the circumstances.
usage: ‘the traveller was fain to proceed’

etym: Hi Anisah! You smell. 10/Sept/2019. CFD are still my bane.
def: In private, in particular taking place in the private chambers of a judge, with the press and public excluded.
usage: ‘judges assess the merits of such claims in camera’

etym: Old English begietan ‘get, obtain by effort’ (see be-, get).
def: (especially of a man) bring (a child) into existence by the process of reproduction.
usage: ‘they hoped that the King might beget an heir by his new queen’

etym: Late 17th century: French, literally ‘blank paper’ (i.e. a blank sheet on which to write whatever one wishes, particularly one's own terms for an agreement).
def: Complete freedom to act as one wishes.
usage: ‘the architect given carte blanche to design the store’

etym: Middle English: from Middle Dutch, Middle Low German schore ‘prop’, of unknown origin.
def: The land along the edge of a sea, lake, or other large body of water.
usage: ‘I made for the shore’

etym: Middle English: from Old English hīgian ‘strive, pant’, of unknown origin.
def: Go quickly.
usage: ‘I hied down to New Orleans’

etym: Late Middle English (in the sense ‘whirl someone or something round’): from late Latin gyrare, from Latin gyrus ‘a ring’, from Greek guros. The noun is from Latin gyrus.
def: Whirl or gyrate.
usage: ‘a swarm of ghosts gyred around him’

etym: Middle English: of Germanic origin; related to German horchen, also to hearken.
def: Listen.
usage: ‘Hark! He knocks’

etym: Latin, ‘in absence’.
def: While not present at the event being referred to.
usage: ‘two foreign suspects will be tried in absentia’

etym: Old English glōmung, from glōm ‘twilight’, of Germanic origin; related to glow.
def: Twilight; dusk.
usage: ‘hundreds of lights are already shimmering in the gloaming’

etym: Latin, from in ‘in’ + extremis, ablative plural of extremus ‘outermost’.
def: In an extremely difficult situation.
usage: ‘one or two would talk to the press in extremis’

etym: Middle English hennes (in hence (sense 3)): from earlier henne (from Old English heonan, of Germanic origin, related to he)+ -s (later respelled -ce to denote the unvoiced sound).
def: As a consequence; for this reason.
usage: ‘many vehicle journeys (and hence a lot of pollution) would be saved’

etym: Latin, ‘by my fault’.
def: Used as an acknowledgement of one's fault or error.
usage: ‘‘Well, whose fault was that?’ ‘Mea culpa!’ Frank said’

etym: 'A sweet thing to eat,' Old English swete mete; see sweet (adj.) + meat (n.).
def: An item of confectionery or sweet food.
usage: ‘he hurried back to his room like a schoolboy who has stolen a sweetmeat’

etym: Middle English (as a verb): from Old French porfil (noun), porfiler (verb), based on Latin pro ‘forward’ + filum ‘thread’.
def: An ornamental border, typically one inlaid on the back or belly of a violin.
usage: ‘close examination of the violin shows that it contains the characteristic purfling’

etym: Mid 19th century (denoting the stone or piece of pottery used in the game): of unknown origin.
def: The game of hopscotch.
usage: ‘those far-off days when they played peevers in the streets’

etym: Old English (as a verb), of West Germanic origin.
def: A narrow gorge or ravine.
usage: ‘I thrutched up the final crack to a small pinnacle’

etym: Mid 19th century: abbreviation of zoological garden, originally applied specifically to that of Regent's Park, London.
def: An establishment which maintains a collection of wild animals, typically in a park or gardens, for study, conservation, or display to the public.
usage: ‘it's a zoo in the lobby’

etym: 'be it as it may, notwithstanding, nevertheless, yet; notwithstanding that,' late 15c., contraction of hough be hit (early 15c.), literally 'how be it.' Compare albeit.
def: Nevertheless; however.
usage: ‘howbeit, I've no proof of the thing’

etym: Old English healtian (verb), halt, healt (adjective), of Germanic origin.
def: Bring or come to an abrupt stop.
usage: ‘there is growing pressure to halt the bloodshed’

etym: Old English wæcce ‘watchfulness’, wæccende ‘remaining awake’; related to wake. The sense ‘small timepiece’ probably developed by way of a sense ‘alarm device attached to a clock’.
def: Look at or observe attentively over a period of time.
usage: ‘Lucy watched him go’

etym: Maori.
def: Used to emphasize how small or insignificant someone or something is.
usage: ‘questions that cannot be answered by mere mortals’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘finely dressed’): from Old French galant, from galer ‘have fun, make a show’, from gale ‘pleasure, rejoicing’.
def: (of a person or their behaviour) brave; heroic.
usage: ‘she had made gallant efforts to pull herself together’

etym: Early 17th century: from Latin degustare, from de- ‘completely’ + gustare ‘to taste’.
def: Taste (something) carefully to appreciate it fully.
usage: ‘Dennis didn't drink it, he degusted it’

etym: Early 18th century: from Latin subfuscus, from sub- ‘somewhat’ + fuscus ‘dark brown’.
def: Dull; gloomy.
usage: ‘the light was subfusc and aqueous’

etym: Late 17th century: Latin, literally ‘by heads’.
def: For each person; in relation to people taken individually.
usage: ‘the state had fewer banks per capita than elsewhere’

etym: 'Hard aromatic seed of the fruit of a tree found in the East Indies,' used as a spice on cookery, c. 1300, note-mug, from Old North French or Anglo-French *noiz mugue, from Old French nois muguete, an unexplained alteration of nois muscade 'nut smelling like musk,' from nois 'nut' (from Latin nux, from PIE *kneu- 'nut;' see nucleus) + Latin muscada, fem. of muscat 'musky' (see muscat). Probably influenced in English by Medieval Latin nux maga (compare unaltered Dutch muskaatnoot, German muscatnuß, Swedish muskotnöt).
def: A wood or forest in leaf (regarded as the typical scene of medieval outlaw life)
usage: ‘the old greenwood adventurers’

etym: Latin, ‘let the buyer beware’.
def: The principle that the buyer alone is responsible for checking the quality and suitability of goods before a purchase is made.
usage: ‘caveat emptor still applies when you are buying your house’

etym: Mid 18th century: from Latin rubescent- ‘reddening’, from the verb rubescere, from ruber ‘red’.
def: Reddening; blushing.
usage: ‘the heart, rubescent and entire’

etym: Old English clūt (in the sense ‘a patch or metal plate’); related to Dutch kluit ‘lump, clod’, also to cleat and clot. The shift of sense to ‘heavy blow’, which dates from late Middle English, is difficult to explain; possibly the change occurred first in the verb (from ‘put a patch on’ to ‘hit hard’).
def: A heavy blow with the hand or a hard object.
usage: ‘a clout round the ear’

etym: Mid 19th century: perhaps from fandango, influenced by newfangle.
def: A useless or purely ornamental thing.
usage: ‘a solo with no end of shakes and trills and fandangles’

etym: Middle English: from Old French fisique ‘medicine’, from Latin physica, from Greek phusikē (epistēmē) ‘(knowledge) of nature’.
def: Medicinal drugs.
usage: ‘his servant's venture into selling physic’

etym: Late 15th century: alteration of obsolete wonders (adjective and adverb), genitive of wonder, on the pattern of marvellous.
def: Inspiring a feeling of wonder or delight; marvellous.
usage: ‘this wondrous city’

etym: Late 17th century: French, literally ‘sweet note’.
def: A love letter.
usage: ‘she was a constant recipient of billets-doux from the boys of the neighbouring school’

etym: Mid 17th century: from blather + skite, a Scots derogatory term adopted into American colloquial speech during the War of Independence from the Scottish song Maggie Lauder, by F. Semphill, which was popular with American troops.
def: A person who talks at great length without making much sense.
usage: ‘politicians get away all the time with obscurantist blatherskite’

etym: Mid 19th century (as a verb): from Pennsylvanian German hexe (verb), Hex (noun), from German hexen (verb), Hexe (noun).
def: Cast a spell on; bewitch.
usage: ‘he hexed her with his fingers’

etym: Late Middle English (denoting a circle): from Latin orbis ‘ring’.
def: A spherical object or shape.
usage: ‘a pale orb of hazy reddish light’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin imminent- ‘overhanging, impending’, from the verb imminere, from in- ‘upon, towards’ + minere ‘to project’.
def: About to happen.
usage: ‘they were in imminent danger of being swept away’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘strike, stab’): of unknown origin.
def: Encircle (a person or part of the body) with a belt or band.
usage: ‘a young man was to be girded with the belt of knighthood’

etym: Latin.
def: Thanks be to God.
usage: ‘Thank you so much, Jeremy. Deo Gratias!’

etym: Mid 17th century: from French, literally ‘fine letters’.
def: Essays, particularly on literary and artistic criticism, written and read primarily for their aesthetic effect.
usage: ‘he inspired me with the desire to restore writing on art to nineteenth century belles-lettres’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin remittere ‘send back, restore’, from re- ‘back’ + mittere ‘send’. The noun dates from the early 20th century.
def: Cancel or refrain from exacting or inflicting (a debt or punishment)
usage: ‘the excess of the sentence over 12 months was remitted’

etym: Late Middle English (as a noun): from Old French bruit ‘noise’, from bruire ‘to roar’.
def: Spread (a report or rumour) widely.
usage: ‘I didn't want to have our relationship bruited about the office’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin, literally ‘receive!’ (first used as an instruction in medical prescriptions), imperative of recipere.
def: A set of instructions for preparing a particular dish, including a list of the ingredients required.
usage: ‘a traditional Yorkshire recipe’

etym: Italian, literally ‘in chapel style’.
def: (with reference to choral music) sung without instrumental accompaniment.
usage: ‘an a cappella Mass’

etym: Middle English: past participle of hight ‘to name or command’, from Old English heht, past tense of hātan ‘to command, call, or name’, of Germanic origin.
def: Named; called.
usage: ‘a little pest, hight Tommy Moore’

etym: Middle English: via Old French from Latin sepultura, from sepelire ‘bury’.
def: Burial; interment.
usage: ‘the rites of sepulture’

etym: Mid 19th century: from French, literally ‘accomplished fact’.
def: A thing that has already happened or been decided before those affected hear about it, leaving them with no option but to accept it.
usage: ‘the results were presented to shareholders as a fait accompli’

etym: Latin, literally ‘under a judge’.
def: Under judicial consideration and therefore prohibited from public discussion elsewhere.
usage: ‘the cases were still sub judice’

etym: Mid 19th century: probably imitative of a whining sound.
def: Pale and sickly in appearance.
usage: ‘his face assumes a peely-wally hue’

etym: Early 17th century: from Latin effabilis, from effari ‘utter’.
def: Able to be described in words.
usage: ‘socialism is effable, which is what I like about it’

etym: Old English þærto 'to it, in that place, for that purpose, belonging to;' see there + to. Similar formation in Old Saxon tharto, Old High German darazuo, German dazu.
def: To that.
usage: ‘his agent thereunto lawfully authorized in writing or by will’

etym: Early 16th century: from medieval Latin comminatorius, from comminat- ‘threatened’, from the verb comminari (see commination).
def: Threatening, punitive, or vengeful.
usage: ‘both advocated a mild resolution which would head off anything more comminatory from the Soviet Union’

etym: Mid 19th century: blend (simulating a Latin form) of abscond, squattle ‘squat down’, and perambulate.
def: Leave abruptly.
usage: ‘some overthrown dictator who had absquatulated to the USA’

etym: Late Middle English (denoting a statement calling attention to something): from Old French advertissement, from the verb advertir (see advertise).
def: A notice or announcement in a public medium promoting a product, service, or event or publicizing a job vacancy.
usage: ‘advertisements for alcoholic drinks’

etym: Old English blīthe, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch blijde, also to bliss.
def: Showing a casual and cheerful indifference considered to be callous or improper.
usage: ‘a blithe disregard for the rules of the road’

etym: Old English seax ‘knife’, of Germanic origin, from an Indo-European root meaning ‘cut’.
def: A saxophone.
usage: ‘alto sax’

etym: Old English lāthlic, from loath + -ly.
def: Causing hatred or disgust; repulsive.
usage: ‘loathly frogs and toads’

etym: French, literally ‘black beast’.
def: A person or thing that one particularly dislikes.
usage: ‘great-uncle Edward was my father's bête noire’

etym: Late Middle English: apparently symbolic of a brief forceful action (compare with jab).
def: A paid position of regular employment.
usage: ‘the scheme could create 200 jobs’

etym: Middle English (as a noun in the senses ‘moderation’, ‘instrument for measuring’, ‘unit of capacity’): from Old French mesure, from Latin mensura, from mens- ‘measured’, from the verb metiri.
def: Ascertain the size, amount, or degree of (something) by using an instrument or device marked in standard units.
usage: ‘the amount of water collected is measured in pints’

etym: 'Close, termination,' 1752, from expire + -y (4). Meaning 'dying, death' is from 1790.
def: The end of the period for which something is valid.
usage: ‘the expiry of the patent’

etym: 1879 in reference to a tennis stroke; 1909 as a noun in this sense; from fore- + hand (n.). Earlier it meant 'position in front or above' (1550s); hence forehanded 'prudent, careful of the future' (1640s), which came to mean 'well-provided, well-to-do,' a sense which lingered in New England into 19c.
def: (in tennis and other racket sports) with a forehand stroke.
usage: ‘a forehanded shot’

etym: Middle English (also in the sense ‘oblige by oath’): from Old French conjurer ‘to plot or exorcise’, from Latin conjurare ‘band together by an oath, conspire’ (in medieval Latin ‘invoke’), from con- ‘together’ + jurare ‘swear’.
def: Cause (a spirit or ghost) to appear by means of a magic ritual.
usage: ‘they hoped to conjure up the spirit of their dead friend’

etym: Old English scrīfan ‘impose as a penance’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch schrijven and German schreiben ‘write’, from Latin scribere ‘write’.
def: (of a priest) hear the confession of, assign penance to, and absolve.
usage: ‘none of her chaplains knew English or French enough to shrive the king’

etym: 'Able to see visions' 1650s (earlier 'perceived in a vision,' 1640s), from vision + -ary. Meaning 'impractical' is attested from 1727. The noun is attested from 1702, from the adjective; originally 'one who indulges in impractical fantasies.'
def: Thinking about or planning the future with imagination or wisdom.
usage: ‘a visionary leader’

etym: In French, 'noblesse oblige' means literally 'nobility obligates.' French speakers transformed the phrase into a noun, which English speakers picked up in the 19th century. Then, as now, 'noblesse oblige' referred to the unwritten obligation of people from a noble ancestry to act honorably and generously to others.
def: Privilege entails responsibility.
usage: ‘the notion of noblesse oblige was part of the ethic of the country gentleman’

etym: Old English on sundran ‘in or into a separate place’; compare with sunder.
def: Apart.
usage: ‘those whom God hath joined together let no man put asunder’

etym: Old English wēnan, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch wanen ‘imagine’, German wähnen ‘suppose wrongly’, also to wish.
def: Be of the opinion; think or suppose.
usage: ‘he, I ween, is no sacred personage’

etym: 'Mechanical broom for sweeping carpets,' 1859, from carpet (n.) + sweeper.
def: An apple of a sweet-flavoured variety.
usage: ‘and all for you, my sweeting’

etym: Late 16th century: Latin, literally ‘according to the rate’.
def: Proportional.
usage: ‘as the pound has fallen costs have risen on a pro rata basis’

etym: Late Old English drūgath ‘dryness’, of Germanic origin; compare with Dutch droogte; related to dry.
def: A prolonged period of abnormally low rainfall, leading to a shortage of water.
usage: ‘the cause of Europe's recent droughts’

etym: Mid 17th century: from late Latin cupreus (from cuprum ‘copper’) + -ous.
def: Of or like copper.
usage: ‘stained green with cupreous patina’

etym: 1940s: abbreviation of facsimile.
def: An exact copy of a document made by electronic scanning and transmitted as data by telecommunications links.
usage: ‘we got a three-page fax from her assistant’

etym: Latin, literally ‘from favour’, from ex ‘from’ and gratia (see grace).
def: (with reference to payment) done from a sense of moral obligation rather than because of any legal requirement.
usage: ‘an ex gratia payment’

etym: 'Puny or contemptible lord,' late 13c., from lord (n.) + -ling.
def: A minor lord.
usage: ‘lordlings do not argue with the Prince of Wales’

etym: Early 18th century: from French barde, a transferred sense of barde ‘armour for the breast and flanks of a warhorse’, based on Arabic barḏa'a ‘saddlecloth, padded saddle’.
def: A poet, traditionally one reciting epics and associated with a particular oral tradition.
usage: ‘our national bard, Robert Burns’

etym: French, literally ‘fine world’.
def: Fashionable society.
usage: ‘London was the centre of this jet-hopping beau monde’

etym: Middle English: from dark + -ling.
def: Growing dark or characterized by darkness.
usage: ‘the darkling sky’

etym: Late Middle English: from Latin rutilant- ‘glowing red’, from the verb rutilare, from rutilus ‘reddish’.
def: Glowing or glittering with red or golden light.
usage: ‘rutilant gems’

etym: Old English gēa, gē, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch and German ja.
def: Yes.
usage: ‘she has the right to say yea or nay’

etym: Mid 18th century: from Latin, literally ‘persons of the drama’.
def: The characters of a play, novel, or narrative.
usage: ‘he has little gift for bringing his dramatis personae to life’

etym: French, literally ‘sweetness’.
def: A financial inducement; a bribe.
usage: ‘Pericles gave a handsome douceur to the Spartan commanders to withdraw without fighting’

etym: Middle English (in trespass (sense 2 of the verb)): from Old French trespasser ‘pass over, trespass’, trespas ‘passing across’, from medieval Latin transpassare (see trans-, pass).
def: Enter someone's land or property without permission.
usage: ‘there is no excuse for trespassing on railway property’

etym: Latin, literally ‘of its own kind’.
def: Unique.
usage: ‘the sui generis nature of animals’

etym: Mid 19th century: named after R. Cox (died 1845), the English amateur fruit grower who first grew it (1825).
def: A coxswain, especially of a racing boat.
usage: ‘the winning eight was coxed by a woman’

etym: Old English gōdlic (see good, -ly).
def: Considerable in size or quantity.
usage: ‘a goodly number of our countrymen’

etym: 'Male deer,' c. 1300, earlier 'male goat;' from Old English bucca 'male goat,' from Proto-Germanic *bukkon (source also of Old Saxon buck, Middle Dutch boc, Dutch bok, Old High German boc, German Bock, Old Norse bokkr), perhaps from a PIE root *bhugo (source also of Avestan buza 'buck, goat,' Armenian buc 'lamb'), but some speculate that it is from a lost pre-Germanic language. Barnhart says Old English buc 'male deer,' listed in some sources, is a 'ghost word or scribal error.' The Germanic word (in the sense 'he-goat') was borrowed in French as bouc.
def: The male of some horned animals, especially the fallow deer, roe deer, reindeer, and antelopes.
usage: ‘the horse seemed to leap, making a mighty buck that shipped the rider off’

etym: 1980s: from flat + line (with reference to the continuous straight line displayed on a heart monitor, indicating death).
def: (of a person) die.
usage: ‘they injected themselves with a deadly drug and flatlined’

etym: 'Made of flax,' mid-15c., from flax + -en (2). As 'of the color of flax' (usually with reference to hair) it is attested from 1520s.
def: Made of flax.
usage: ‘her long flaxen hair’

etym: Mid 17th century: from Latin caeruleus ‘sky blue’, from caelum ‘sky’.
def: Deep blue in colour like a clear sky.
usage: ‘images of cerulean waters and golden sands’

etym: Snake +‎ bitten.
def: Doomed to misfortune; unlucky.
usage: ‘the snakebitten space shuttle chalked up a fourth launch delay’

etym: Middle English (in the sense ‘made to fit’): shortening of Old English gemǣte, of Germanic origin; related to mete.
def: Arrange or happen to come into the presence or company of (someone)
usage: ‘a week later I met him in the street’

etym: Latin.
def: A first among equals; the senior or representative member of a group.
usage: ‘the feudal king was primus inter pares among his vassals’

etym: Late Middle English: early form of Bethlehem, referring to the hospital of St Mary of Bethlehem in London, used as an institution for the insane.
def: A scene of uproar and confusion.
usage: ‘there was bedlam in the courtroom’

etym: Old English bana ‘thing causing death, poison’, of Germanic origin.
def: A cause of great distress or annoyance.
usage: ‘the telephone was the bane of my life’

etym: Old English rendan; related to Middle Low German rende.
def: Tear (something) into pieces.
usage: ‘snapping teeth that would rend human flesh to shreds’

etym: Old English brēc (plural of brōc, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch broek), interpreted as a singular form. The original sense was ‘garment covering the loins and thighs’ (compare with breeches), hence ‘the buttocks’ ( breech (sense 2 of the noun), mid 16th century), later ‘the hind part’ of anything.
def: The part of a cannon behind the bore.
usage: ‘the 47-round ammunition drum fits over the breech’

etym: Middle English: from Old French sanz, from a variant of Latin sine ‘without’, influenced by Latin absentia ‘in the absence of’.
def: Without.
usage: ‘a picture of Maughan sans specs’

etym: 'One who holds a doctrine at variance with established or dominant standards,' mid-14c., from Old French eretique (14c., Modern French hérétique), from Church Latin haereticus 'of or belonging to a heresy,' as a noun, 'a heretic,' from Greek hairetikos 'able to choose' (in the New Testament, 'heretical'), verbal adjective of hairein 'to take' (see heresy).
def: As a result of this.
usage: ‘greatly distressed hereat, they declared themselves to deserve a fine’

etym: French, literally ‘I do not know what’.
def: A quality that cannot be described or named easily.
usage: ‘that je ne sais quoi which makes a professional’

etym: From Middle English twelmonth, twelfmonthe, twelfmonþe, from Old English twelfmōnþ, twelfmōnaþ, equivalent to twelve +‎ month.
def: A year.
usage: ‘the summer forenoon seemed a twelvemonth long’

etym: From ergo- +‎ -meter.
def: An apparatus which measures work or energy expended during a period of physical exercise.
usage: ‘the subject's anaerobic power was determined by having them pedal a bicycle ergometer’

etym: Old English mōna, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch maan and German Mond, also to month, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin mensis and Greek mēn ‘month’, and also Latin metiri ‘to measure’ (the moon being used to measure time).
def: The natural satellite of the earth, visible (chiefly at night) by reflected light from the sun.
usage: ‘there was no moon, but a sky sparkling with brilliant stars’

etym: Old English hwīlum ‘at times’, dative plural of hwīl (see while).
def: Formerly; in the past.
usage: ‘the wistful eyes which whilom glanced down upon the fields’

etym: Mid 19th century: from Latin succuss- ‘shaken’, from the verb succutere, from sub- ‘away’ + quatere ‘to shake’.
def: (in preparing homeopathic remedies) shake (a solution) vigorously.
usage: ‘a drop of 1 c solution is diluted and then succussed again’

etym: Old English oferhlēapan (see over, leap).
def: Jump over or across.
usage: ‘a stream that any five-years' child might overleap’

etym: Middle English (denoting both physical and mental pain or distress): via Old French from Latin dolor ‘pain, grief’.
def: A state of great sorrow or distress.
usage: ‘they squatted, hunched in their habitual dolour’

etym: Early 17th century (in the sense ‘flatter, pretend to agree with or believe’): probably an alteration of obsolete colleague ‘conspire’, by association with Latin colloqui ‘to converse’.
def: Talk confidentially or conspiratorially.
usage: ‘they wagged their old heads sadly when they collogued in clubs’

etym: French, literally ‘allow to do’.
def: The policy of leaving things to take their own course, without interfering.
usage: ‘a laissez-faire attitude to life’

etym: Early 20th century: French, literally ‘disastrous woman’.
def: An attractive and seductive woman, especially one who will ultimately cause distress to a man who becomes involved with her.
usage: ‘a femme fatale who plays one man off against another in pursuit of money’

etym: Aristotle comes from the ancient Greek Αριστοτελης meaning 'the best end', derived from the 'elements' αριστος (aristos) 'best' and τελος (telos) 'end, consummation, aim, goal, perfection,' literally “completion of a cycle.”.
def: A bottle.
usage: ‘it was his fourth for the morning by the look of the three empty aristotles rolling around on the car floor’

etym: Late 16th century: alteration of late Middle English bass (noun and verb), probably from French baiser, from Latin basiare.
def: A kiss.
usage: ‘he bussed her on the cheek’

etym: Old English lafian, from Latin lavare ‘to wash’; reinforced in Middle English by Old French laver.
def: Wash.
usage: ‘she ran cold water in the basin, laving her face and hands’

etym: Late 19th century: French, literally ‘last cry’.
def: The very latest fashion.
usage: ‘as soon as he was passé on the European scene, he became the dernier cri here’

etym: Early 19th century (originally denoting a member of the Irish constabulary): from the name of Sir Robert Peel, Sir Robert.
def: A knife or device for removing the skin from fruit and vegetables.
usage: ‘a potato peeler’

etym: Late 18th century: from Latin otiosus, from otium ‘leisure’.
def: Serving no practical purpose or result.
usage: ‘there were occasions when I felt my efforts were rather otiose’

etym: Middle English (denoting a trick or pretence): perhaps via Anglo-Norman French from Old French gaudir ‘rejoice’, from Latin gaudere; perhaps influenced by obsolete gaud ‘ornamental bead in a rosary’.
def: A showy and purely ornamental thing.
usage: ‘displays of overpriced gauds’

etym: Late Middle English: perhaps a back-formation from striped, of Dutch or Low German origin; compare with Middle Dutch and Middle Low German strīpe.
def: A long, narrow band or strip differing in colour or texture from the surface on either side of it.
usage: ‘a pair of blue shorts with pink stripes’

etym: Middle English: from Old French, literally ‘surrendering’, present participle of recroire, from medieval Latin (se) recredere ‘surrender (oneself)’, from re- (expressing reversal) + credere ‘entrust’.
def: Cowardly.
usage: ‘what a recreant figure must he make’

etym: Old English lēa(h), of Germanic origin; related to Old High German loh ‘grove’, from an Indo-European root shared by Sanskrit lokás ‘open space’, Latin lucus ‘grove’, and perhaps also light.
def: An open area of grassy or arable land.
usage: ‘the lowing herd winds slowly o'er the lea’

etym: Late 16th century: Latin, ‘from what is before’.
def: Relating to or denoting reasoning or knowledge which proceeds from theoretical deduction rather than from observation or experience.
usage: ‘a priori assumptions about human nature’

etym: Middle English: abbreviation of maiden.
def: A female domestic servant.
usage: ‘Mary eventually managed to find a job as a maid’

etym: Mid 17th century: from French déglutition or modern Latin deglutitio(n-), from deglutire ‘swallow down’.
def: The action or process of swallowing.
usage: ‘the muscles involved in deglutition’

etym: Early 17th century: apparently a weakened form of obsolete cond ‘conduct, guide’, from Old French conduire, from Latin conducere (see conduce).
def: Persuade (someone) to do or believe something by lying to them.
usage: ‘I conned him into giving me your home number’

etym: Latin.
def: God willing; if nothing prevents it.
usage: ‘she has signed the lease for the house—it will be for both of them, Deo volente’
